column168: Description Of Events
SHIPMENT WAS UNLOADED SITTING ON THE DOCK AND WAS STRUCK AND PUNCTURED WITH THE FORK OF A LIFT TRUCK.  MORE CAUTION SHOULD HAVE BEEN USED WHEN OPERATING LIFT TRUCK.
DRIVER WAS UNLOADING AND CUSTOMER HAD A CRACK IN THERE PIPE.  CAUSING A LEAK.
THE FRANGIBLE DISC WAS DISCOVERED BLOWN RIGHT AFTER THE CAR GOING THROUGH A CLASSIFICATION YARD.  THE DISC WAS REPLACED IN KIND AND THE CAR DECONTAMINATED, THEN RELEASED THE TRANSPORTATION.

RAILCAR TGIX 1108 ABOUT 2 WEEKS BEFORE HAD LEAKING VALVE.  IO ENTERPRIZE SENT CAR IN FOR REPAIRS WITH ONE LOAD IN CAR.  CAR WAS CHECKED OUT BY IO ENTERPRISE AND NO ONE WAS TOLD CAR STILL HAD LOAD IN IT.  DRIVER MARK EACH LOAD PUT IN CAR AND SHOWED TO BE ONLY 3 LOADS IN CAR BUT WITH LOAD STILL IN CAR MADE 4 LOADS.  DRIVERS WILL LOOK DOWN IN CARS FROM NOW ON. SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN SMALL AREA AND CLEAN UP.

THE MORNING OF 9-3-91 LARRY BAKER CALL FROM THE LINDE OFFICE AND TOLD ME THERE WAS A LEAK IN OR ATC UNIT IT SPRAYED THE INSIDE OF THE BUILDING, WE PUMPED TWO LOADS THRU THE ATC UNIT AND DIDN'T FIND THE LEAK.  THE DRIVERS WILL WATCH IT WHEN THEY UNLOAD.

ABOVE CONDITIONS COMBINED TO ALLOW PRODUCT TO ESCAPE CAR WHILE IN MOTION.  ALL VALVES, HANDLE AND PLUGS SECURED.  CAR SAFE FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

PACKAGE  WAS FOUND ON HARBOR BOX LINE.  ONE OF FOUR FOUR LITRE BOTTLES HAD BROKEN FROM THE FALL. THE COMPLETE PACKAGE WAS REPACKAGED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.

THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND LEAKING ON ONE OF THE BELTS.  A ONE QUART HAD BEEN CRUSHED AND BROKEN OPEN.  THE ENTIRE SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED AND NOTHING RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.   THE DAMAGED CARTONS AND CONTENTS WERE DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO UPS SPECIFICATIONS.  A DAMAGE REPORT WAS WRITTEN AND AN ISP CARD WAS SENT TO THE ORIGIN DISTRICT FOR FOLLOW-UP WITH THE SHIPPER.
PACKAGE WAS DROPPED IN HANDLING.  DAMAGED PORTION DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PROCEDURE.  UNDAMAGED PORTION WAS RETURNED.  MORE PACKAGE HANDLING AUDITS SHOULD BE PERFORMED.

LOOSE CAP CAUSED LEAK.  PACKAHE CONTAINED EIGHT PINT BOTTLES IN TOW CARTONS TAPED TOGETHER TO FROM A BUNDLE.  SHIPMENT WAS CONCEALED.  PACKAGE CONTAINED NO 5-PART OR CORROSIVE DIAMOND LABEL.  LABEL ON PACKAGE WAS CARTON INDICATED UN1790.  CUSTOMER SERVICE SHOULD VISIT THIS SHIPPER ASAP AND EXPLAIN PROPER PROCEDURE FOR SHIPPING HYDROFLUORIC ACID VIA PARCEL SERVICE.

CAR WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING OUT BOTTOM OF CAR WHILE BEING INSPECTED IN TRACK 6 AND WAS PLACED TO AN ISOLATED TRACK FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIRS. SHIPPER, CHEMTREC AND BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES WERE NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER ADVISED REPAIRMAN WOULD BE SENT TO YARD TO MAKE INSPECTION AND REPAIRS.  AFTER INSPECTION IT WAS DETERMINED CAR WAS LEAKING BETWEEN BOTTOM VALVE AND TANK CAR AND REPAIRS WERE UNABLE TO BE DONE, CAR WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER FOR THEIR HANDLING.

WHILE UNLOADING NO 2 FUEL OIL DRIVER STARTED TO REMOVE THE CAP FROM THE #3 DISCHARGE PIPE AND FAILED TO NOTICE THAT THE #3 DISCHARGE VALVE HAD BEEN LEFT IN THE OPEN POSITION.  AS THE CAP CAME OFF AND OIL STARTED COMING OUT, THE DISCHARGE VALVE WAS IMMEDIATELY CLOSED RESULTING IN A SPILL OF APPROX. 5 GAL.  RAGS AND SPILL PADS WERE IMMEDIATELY APPLIED TO LOW SIDE OF SPILL TO DIKE AND CONTAIN SPILL AGAINST CURB.  THEN SPEEDY DRY AND MORE SPILL PADS WERE APPLIED TO ABSORB THE OIL.

column168: ON SEPTEMBER 10, 1991 APPROXIMATELY 0115 CENTRAL TIME VEHICLE #1 WAS PROCEEDING SOUTH ON I55 NEAR MILE MARKER 230.  VEHICLE #1 WAS TRAVELING APPROXIMATELY 55 MPH WHEN DRIVER OF VEHICLE #1 HEARD A LOUD NOISE AND IMMEIDATELY THE STEERING WHEEL WAS JERKED OUT OF THE DRIVER'S HANDS. VEHICLE #1 VEERED SHARPLY TO THE RIGHT, WENT INTO A CONSTRUCTION SITE WHERE THE CONCRETE HAD BEEN TORN UP.  WHEN THE UNIT WENT DOWN INTO THE HOLES THE UNDER CARRIAGE OF TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE SEVERELY DAMAGED. AIR LINES BROKEN BETWEEN TRACTOR AND TRAILER CAUSING BRAKES ON TRAILER TO SET UP.  UNIT CAME TO A REST AGAINST GUARDRAIL ON RIGHT SHOULDER AND TRAILER OVERTURNED.  TANDEMS OF THE TRAILER  STRUCK AND BENT VALVE STEM ALLOWING A SMALL LEAK.

LOAD WAS ON NINE PALLETS EACH SHRINK WRAPPED.  BELIEVED THAT EXTREME HEAT IN TRAILER, FROM 90 DEG AND OUTSIDE TEMPERATURE, CAUSED PLASTIC WRAP TO STRETCH ALLOWING CONTAINERS TO TIP OVER.  WHEN LEAK WAS DETECTED ABSORBANT WAS APPLIED TO PREVENT FURTHER LOSS.  FREIGHT WAS OFF LOADED UP-RIGHTED AND RELOADED FOR DELIVERY TO CONSIGNEE.  TRAILERWAS CLEANED FOLLOWING INSTRUCTIONS FROM SHIPPER.

column168: DRIVERS LEFT GLENMONT, NY WITH TRAILER #13014, WHICH WAS EMPTY, BOUND FOR SARNIA, ONTARIO CANADA.  WHILE DRIVEING ON HWY #402 AT THE INTERCHANGE WIHT HWY. 40 IN SARNIA, THE TRAILER STARTED TO VENT.  DRIVERS PULLED OVER AND CHECKED TRAILER AND PRESSURE GAUGES.  PRESSURES WAS AT 55 LBS.  VAPOR VENTED FOR ABOUT (1) MINUTE AND STOPPED AT 38LBS.  DRIVERS PROCEEDED TO AIR PRODUCTS SARNIA PLANT WHICH WAS ONLY MINUTES AWAY.  AT SARNIA AT WAS DETERMINED THAT TRAILER LOST VACUUM. TRAILER WAS WARMED UP WITH WARM GAS AND PURGED WITH INERT NITROGEN AND SENT TO NORTH BALTIMORE, OHIO.  THEY AGAIN TESTED TRAILER FOR VACUUM AND FOUND THAT IT DID NOT HOLD.  TRAILER WILL BE TESTED TRAILER FOR VACUUM AND FOUND THAT IT DID NOT HOLD.  TRAILER WILL BE TRANSPORTED TO AIR PRODUCTS, NEW ORLEANS TERMINAL FOR EVALUATION AND REPAIRS BEFORE RETURNING TO SERVICE.

IT IS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY FIVE POUNDS OF AMMONIA MAY HAVE BEEN RELEASED.  NO KNOWN INJURIES OR DAMAGES.  THIS CARGO TANK PASSED A LEAKAGE TEST ON 8-26-91.

LAROCHE DRIVER WAS IN PROCESS OF LOADING MC331 CARGO TANK WITH ANHYDROUS AMMONIA AT LAROCHE DISTRIBUTION CENTER IN E. ST. LOUIS, IL.  DURING THE LOADING PROCESS APPROXIMATELY 18 POUNDS OF AMMONIA WAS RELEASED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE WHEN A VALVE ON THE STORAGE TANK PIPING FAILED TO HOLD.  THE LOADING PROCEDURE WAS STOPPED AND VALVE REPAIRED AND SECURED WITH STEEL CAP.  THE RELEASE DID NOT SPECIFICALLY INVOLVE THE MC331 CARGO TANK AND THIS PACKAGE DID NOT FAIL.  NO KNOW INJURIES OR DAMAGES.

DRIVER ARRIVED AT LAROCHE TERMINAL IN KANSAS CITY AT 4:00 A.M. AND NOTICED AMMONIA LEAKING FROM METER ON TRANSPORT TRAILER.  USING A COMPRESSOR AT THE FACILITY, HE EVACUATED WHATEVER QUANTITY OF AMMONIA MAY HAVE BEEN IN PUMP, PIPING AND HOSE.  THE MAXIMUM AMOUNT THAT COULD HAVE BEEN RETAINED AND RELEASED WOULD HAVE BEEN 21 POUNDS.  THE METER WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE AND REPAIRED. THIS METER HAD BEEN REBUILT BY LIQUID CONTROLS FOLLOWING A SIMILAR LEAK ON 9-6-91.  APPARENTLY THE WRONG PLATES HAD BEEN INSTALLED CAUSING THE LEAK ON 9-12-91.  THE CORRECT PARTS HAVE NOW BEEN INSTALLED AND THE METER RETURNED TO SERVICE.

DRIVER BEGAN UNLOADING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA THROUGH 1" DELIVERY HOSE INTO CUSTOMER REFRIGERATION SYSTEM.  A LEAK DEVELOPED AT THE METER, THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE PUMP AND CLOSED THE FISHER INTERNAL VALVE ON THE CARGO TANK.  APPROXIMATELY 21 POUNDS OF AMMONIA THAT HAD BEEN RETAINED IN HOSE, PIPING, PUMP AND METER WAS RELEASSED.  THE DRIVER REMOVED THE METER FROM SERVICE AND USED A BY-PASS TO COMPLETE THE DELIVERY.  THIS METER HAD BEEN RE-WORKED IN CONJUNCTION WITH LEAKAGE TEST ON 8-30-91.  INSPECTION OF THE METER DETERMINED THAT THE PLATE HAD CRACKED.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: RELEVANT MATERIAL CONSISTED OF OUTER DOUBLE-WALLED CORRUGATED FIBERBOARD BOXES EACH CONTAINING ONE 5 GALLON PLASTIC BLADDER OF 10% BUFFERED FORMALIN (A 3.7% BIO-DEGRADABLE FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTION).  THE BOXES WERE STRETCH WRAPPED WITH PLASTIC FILM TO WOODEN PALLETS.  THIS WAS THE ONLY SHIPMENT ON THE TRAILER.  TWO PALLETS OF THE BOXES NEAR THE REAR OF THE TRAILER TIPPED OVER APPARENTLY WHEN THE VEHICLE MADE A TURN, AND THE IMPACT APPARENTLY CAUSED TWO 5 GALLON BLADDERS INSIDE OF TWO BOXES TO BURST AND THE FORMALIN INSIDE OF TWO BOXES TO SPILL ONTO AND SOAK INTO OTHER FIBERBOARD BOXES IN THE PALLETS AND ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. WHEN THE PICK-UP DRIVER TOOK THE TRAILER TO THE STORAGE LOT OF THE TERMINAL FACILITY AT ROMULUS, MI, AND WALKED TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER, HE DETECTED A VERY STRANGE ODOR COMING FROM THE TRAILER AND OPENED IT'S DOOR AND DISCOVERED THE PROBLEM AND NOTIFIED THE MANAGER AT THE ROMULUS AGENCY TERMINAL. INFOTRAK WAS IMMEDIATELY CALLED FOR RESPONSE INFORMATION.  THE ROMULUS FIRE DEPT. WAS ALSO CALLED, WHOSE HAZ-MAT TEAM CAME TO THE TERMINAL TO ASSIST.  THE SPILLED FORMALIN WAS CONTAINED AND ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY (GROUND CLAY).  THE STRETCH WRAP WAS REMOVED FROM THE TIPPED PALLETS.  THE UNHARMED BOXES WRE RESTRETCH-WRAPPED ONTO PALLETS.  IT WAS THEN DETERMINED THAT 30 DAMAGED BOXES HAD THEIR PLASTIC BLADDERS IN TACT AND WERE NOT LEAKING AND THAT TWO 5 GALLON BLADDERS HAD BURST AND WERE EMPTY.  THE OIL DRY AND SOAKED BOXES WERE PACKAGED AND SEALED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND TRANSPORTED BY SBFL TO IT'S HOME TERMIAL FOR PROPER DISPOSAL AS AN EXEMPT U122 WASTE PURSUANT TO EXCLUSION FOR SMALL QUANTITY GENERATION.  THE 30 IN TACT, 5 GALLON UNITS OF FOMALIN WERE PICKED UP AT THE ROMULUS TERMINAL BY THE SHIPPER, MICHCLONE ASSOCIATES, INC. ALTHOUGH IT DOES NOT APPEAR THAT THE REGULATIONS REQUIRE THAT AN INCIDENT REPORT BE MADE TO THE DOT OF THIS VERY MINOR SPILL OF AN ORM-A MATERIAL, THIS REPORT IS BEING SUBMITTED BECAUSE OF THE PRECAUTIONARY CONTACT AND INVOLVEMENT OF INFOTRAK AND ROMULUS FIRE DEPT.

55 GALLON DRUMS WERE BEING TRANSFERRED FROM A TRANSPORTATION TRUCK TO A PHOENIX TRUCK.  DURING THE PROCESS, A CWM EMPLOYEE PUNCTURED ONE 55 GALLON DRUM WITH A MATERIAL HANDLING DEVICE.  APPROXIMATELY 2-3 GALLONS OF WASTE COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND.  THIS IS A NON-RQ AND NEEDS TO BE REPORTED TO D.O.T. AS AN INCIDENT DURING TRANSFER OR UNLOADING OF WASTE. THE DRUM WAS POSITIONED UPRIGHT IMMEDIATELY; THE WASTE WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP PROMPTLY; AND THE EMPLOYEE WAS RE-TRAINED ON PROPER HANDLING OF WASTE AND RECEIVED EMPLOYEE'S DISCIPLINARY COUNSELING.

column168: DRIVER #1 WAS APPARENTLY TRAVELLING TOO FAST UPON APPROACHING A CURVE. DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE ON THE CURVE, CAUSING THE TRACTOR TO RUM OFF OF THE ROAD, OVERTURNING THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER,  APPROXIMATELY 65-70 GALLONS OF ACETONE WAS LOST DUE TO A SMALL LEAK ON A VALVE/FITTING THAT WAS DAMAGED IN THE ACCIDENT.  IMMEDIATELY THE DARLINGTON FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE, RESPONDING WITH 2 FIRE ENGINES, FIREFIGHTERS, RESCUE UNITS AND THE LOACL SHERIFF DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL.  A COMMAND POST WAS SET UP 700 FEET UPWIND FROM THE ACCIDENT WITH THE FIREFIGHTERS CLOSING OFF THE ACCIDENT AREA.  THE DNR WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SITUATION. A TRENCH WAS DUG AROUND THE LOWER SIDE OF THE TANK TO PREVENT ANY MATERIAL FROM SPREADING.  ALL VALVES WERE SHUT OFF AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.  NO INJURIES WERE REPORTED.

DOCKMAN WAS UNLOADING TRAILER AND SMELLED A STRONG ODOR IN TRAILER.  HE STOPPED AND CHECKED HIS D.R.s, AND FOUND THAT HE HAD SOME H.M. ON BOARD TRAILER.  HE NOTIFIED SUPEVISOR AND SUPERVISOR CHECKED EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE BOOK, CALLED SHIPPER AND REQUESTED MSDS SHEETS, AND NOTIFIED SAFETY DEPARTMENT OF POSSIBLE LEAK.  PAPER WORK AND MSDS SHEETS WERE CHECKED TO SEE IF IT WAS SAFE TO SECURE THIS PRODUCT.  LIDS WERE PLACED BACK ONTO CONTAINERS.  SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY REQUESTED THAT WE SHIP PRODUCT BACAK TO THEM IF IT WAS NOT LEAKING.  PRODUCT WAS AND WOULD NOT LEAK ONCE LIDS WERE REPLACE ON CONTAINERS.  FREIGHT WILL BE FORWARED BACK TO SHIPPER.  WHAT CAUSED DAMAGE TO THIS FREIGHT WAS IMPROPER LOADING BY ORIGIN SERVICE CENTER.  FREIGHT HAD FALLEN AND HIT CANS CAUSING LIDS TO POP OFF CANS.  PREVENTION WOULD BE TO MAKE SURE LOADS WERE SECURED IN TRAILER TO PREVENT MOVEMENT IN TRANSIT.  AS IN ALL CANS WHERE LIDS A ONLY SECURED BY PRESSURE THIS WILL ALWAYS BE A PROBELM WITH DAMAGED AND LEAKAGE.  SLIGHT PRESSURE ON THE SIDES OF THIS TYPE OF CONTAINER WILL CAUSE THE LID TO POP OFF VERY EASILY.

WE CONTACTED ORIGIN SERVICE CENTER AND ADVISED THEM TO BE MORE CAREFUL WHEN USING FORKLIFT WHEN LOADING PALLETS SO THAT THE SAM INCIDENT WOUL NOT HAPPEN AGAIN.  PACKAGING IS NOT THE PROBLEM HERE. column168: 2 CYLINDERS WERE LOADED AND BOTH HAD 4X4'S NAILED TO FLOOR TO KEEP THEM FROM MOVING.  THE BACK BOARD ON ONE OF THE CYLINDERS WAS KNOCKED LOOSE ENROUTE.  I WENT TO FLECT AT OAK ST TO MAKE A DELIVERY AND HAD TO BACK ON AT FLECT AT AN ANGLE.  CYLINDERS WERE LOADED ON DRIVERS SIDE OF TRAILER AND THIS SIDE WAS HIGHER THAN OTHER SIDE DUE TO BACKING IN AT ANGEL AND POSSIBLY CAUSED THIS CYLINDER STARTED LEAKING.  WHEN I OPENED BY DOORS AT FLECT AND REALIZED THIS A CALLED BILL MOBILE OFFICE AND HE ADVISED ME TO MAKE SURE MY DOORS WERE CLOSED GOOD AND TO KEEP ANYONE AWAY FROM UNIT.  HE ADVISED HE WOULD CONTACT RIEDEL PETERSON.  RIEDEL PETERSON DID NOT HAVE PEOPLE TO SEND BUT ADVISED WE COULD JUST CONTACT THE FIRE DEPT.  BILL ADV ME TO MOVE TRAILER FROM DOCK TO A DESERTED PLACE. TWO TRUCKS CONTAINER 23 RADIOACTIVE SEALED SOURCES THAT WERE BEING TRANSFERRED TO ATLAS WIRELINE SERVICES' HEADQUARTERS IN HOUSTON, TEXAS FOR STORAGE.  THE LOGGING ENGINEER/SUPERVISOR WHO SUPERVISED THE TRANSFER FOLLOWED THE TRUCKS IN A CAR.  THE CONVOY STOPPED AT AN OKLAHOMA HIGHWAY DEPARTMENT WEIGH STATION ON INTERSTATE 35 OUTSIDE DAVIS, OKLAHOMA AND PROCEEDED TO ATLAS WIRELINE SERVICES' FACILITY LOCATED AT U.S. HIGHWAY 70 AND INTERSTATE 35 AT ARDMORE, OKLAHOMA.  AN ADDITIONAL TRUCK JOINED THE CONVOY AT 0430 HRS.  THE CONVOY PROCEEDED TO THE VICINITY OF CORSICANA, TEXAS WHERE IT ENCOUNTERED A SEVERE RAINSTORM WHICH CONTAINED TO HOUSTON, TEXAS.  AS THE CONVOY WAS EXITING INTERSTATE 45 AND WAS TURNING LEFT BENEATH THE UNDERPASS ON U.S. 75 AT APPROXIMATELY 1030 HRS, ONE OF THE TRUCKS FROM YUKON, OKLAHOMA LOST A 2 CURIE CS-137 SEALED SOURCE (SOURCE SERIAL NUMBER 899, MODEL S3T20) USED FOR FORMATION DENSITY MEASUREMENTS IN OIL/GAS WELL LOGGING ACTIVITIES. THE SOURCE WAS IN A TYPE A SHIPPING CONTAINER, ATLAS WIRELINE SERVICES PART NUMBER 080729.  THE CONVOY CONTINUED TO HOUSTON NOT REALIZING THAT A SOURCE HAD BEEN LOST UNTIL ARRIVAL AT THE ATLAS WIRELINE SERVICES FACILITY IN HOUSTON TEXAS. THE TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH WAS NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY.  THE NUCLEAR REGULATORY COMMISSION WAS NOTIFIED AT APPROXIMATELY 1500 HRS.  ATLAS WIRELINE SERVICES INITIATED A SEARCH FOR THE SOURCE BETWEEN 1330 HRS AND 1400 HRS ON SEPTEMBER 5, 1991 FROM THE HOUSTON END OF THE ROUTE SEARCH NORTH AND FROM THE YUKON END OF THE ROUTE TO SEARCH SOUTH TO ARMORE, OKLAHOMA.  ONE MEMBER LEFT ARDMORE TO SEARCH SOUTH TO THE TEXAS STATE LINE.  THE TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH INFORMED ME THAT A DEPARTMENT INSPECTOR WAS SEARCHING THE HIGHWAY FROM DALLAS NORTH TO THE OKLAHOMA STATE LINE.  AN ADDITIONAL ATLAS WIRELINE SERVICES SAFETY ENGINEER WAS FLOWN TO DALLAS, TEXAS TO SEARCH FROM DALLAS SOUTH TO MET THE HOUSTON SEARCH PARTY.  HOWEVER, THE SOURCE WAS LOCATED PRIOR TO THE INITIATION OF THIS LEG OF THE SEARCH.  THE SEARCH PARTIES WERE EQUIPPED WITH RADIATION DETECTION INSTRUMENTS CAPABLE OF LOCATING THE LOST SOURCE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1730 HRS ON THURSDAY, SEPTEMBER 5, 1991 A CITIZEN SAW THE SHIPPING CONTAINER LYING ON THE GRAVEL SHOULDER ABOUT 30 FEET FROM THE SOUTHEAST CORNER OF INTERSECTION OF U.S. 70 AND I-45.  THE SOURCE WAS LOCATED NEAR THE UNDERPASS ON I-70 AND THE TYPE A TRANSPORT SHIELD CONTAINER WAS ABOUT 3 TO 4 FEET FROM THE SOURCE.

THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, DEPUTY SHERIFF AND A KENTUCKY STATE TROOPER INSPECTED THE SCENE AND THEN INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO RETURN TO PASCHALL TRUCK LINES' TERMINAL IN MURRAY, KENTUCKY.

ON WEDNESDAY, SEPTEMBER 25, 1991, OUR DRIVER WAS PICKING UP A ROLL-OFF CONTAINER AT CENTRAL BRASS IN CLEVELAND, OHIO.  WHEN PICKING UP AT CENTRAL BRASS, THE DRIVER MUST SET THE EMPTY CAN DOWN AND PULL THE LOADED CAN OF FOUNDRY SAND OUT OF THE LOCATION IN ORDER TO PLACE THE EMPTY CAN IN THE PROPER LOADING AREA.  WHEN THE DRIVER WAS SETTING THE LOADED CAN DOWN, APPROXIMATELY 100 POUNDS OF MATERIAL SPILLED OUT OF THE CAN BETWEEN THE TOP OF THE CAN AND THE TARP.  THE MATERIAL SPILLED ONTO A GRAVEL PARKING AREA AT THE CUSTOMER SITE.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP BY OUR DRIVER AND AN EMPLOYEE OF CENTRAL BRASS WITH FLOOR DRY AND PUT BACK INTO THE CONTAINER. THERE WAS NO LEAKING OF THE MATERIAL FROM THE CAN AND THEREFORE, THE LOADED CAN WAS TRANSPORTED SAFELY BACK TO THE ENVIRITE FACILITY.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1100 HOURS, FRIDAY, SEPTEMBER 27, 1991, A YARD TRAIN CREW SWITCHING RAIL CARS AT THE CONRAIL COLUMBUS, OHIO RAIL YARD OBSERVED LIQUID PRODUCT NEAR THE TOP VALVE AREA OF TANK CAR GATX-10328.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.  ALSO NOTIFIED WAS DOT/FRA HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INSPECTOR J. CONNELLY WHO WAS PRESENT AT THE RAIL YARD. RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM SIMPSON AND SONS, REPRESENTING THE SHIPPER, ARRIVED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CAR AT APPROXIMATELY 2025 HOURS, SEPTEMBER 27, 1991 AND UPON INSPECTION DISCOVERED A RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISK IN THE TANK CAR'S SAFETY VENT.  RUPTURED DISK WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH A NEW DISK.  CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT APPROXIMATELY 2130 HOURS, SEPTEMBER 27, 1991. A SECOND TANK CAR, GATX-48780, WAS ALSO INSPECTED ON THE REQUEST OF DOT/FRA INSPECTOR CONNELLY WHEN IT WAS THOUGHT THAT THIS CAR MIGHT ALSO BE LEAKING PRODUCT.  CAR WAS INSPECTED BY CONRAIL MECHANICAL SUPERVISION AND NO LEAK OR RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISK WAS FOUND.

THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE PRIMARY SORT.  ONE OF THE FOUR ONE GALLON BOTTLES HAD A LOOSE CAP.  THE CARTON WAS REPACKED ACCORDING TO UPS SPECIFICATIONS AND SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.  A DAMAGE REPORT WAS WRITTEN AND AN ISP CARD SENT TO THE ORIGIN DISTRICT FOR FOLLOW-UP WITH THE SHIPPER.

THE PARCEL WAS FOUND WHILE UNLOADING DURING THE PRELOAD.  THE PARCEL WAS TAKEN TO THE RE-WRAP AREA FOR PROCESSING.  THE PACKAGE WAS OPENED AND FOUND THAT ONE OF THE SIX ADHESIVES WAS SHIPPED WITHOUT CLIPS ON THE CAN. THE REMAINING CANS WERE REPACKED ACCORDING TO UPS SPECIFICATIONS AND SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER. A DAMAGE REPORT WAS WRITTEN AND AN ISP CARD SENT TO THE ORIGIN DISTRICT FOR FOLLOW UP WITH THE SHIPPER.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1045 HOURS, MONDAY, SEPTEMBER 16, 1991, A DRIVER FOR PRESTON TRUCKING REPORTED TO SUPERVISIOR AT THE CONRAIL, HARRISBURG, PA INTERMODAL TERMINAL, THAT TRAILER XTRZ-683609 WAS LEAKING A LIQUID PRODUCT THAT APPEARED TO BE PAINT. TRAILER WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM PRESTON TRUCKING ARRIVED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TRAILER AT 1310 HOURS, 06/19/91, AND UPON INSPECTION, FOUND THAT ONE 55 GALLON DRUM OF PAINT WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM A HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM WHICH APPARENTLY HAD BEEN CREATED WHEN THE DRUM WAS LOADED INTO THE TRAILER. RESPONSE PERSONNEL PATCHED LEAK AND PLACED DRUM INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM ALONG WITH APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF THICK PAINT THAT HAD SEEPED FROM THE DRUM. AT APPROXIMATELY 4:35 PM RECEIVED A CALL FROM MY DRIVER FRANK RAYMOND WHICH NOTICED HIS TRAILER DOOR OPEN AND FREIGHT MISSING AT A CUSTOMERS DOCK AS HE HAD JUST PULLED UP TO THE DOCK.  I THEN INSTRUCTED FRANK TO RE-TRACK HIS ROUTE TO LOCATE CONTAINER.  AT APPROXIMATELY 4:45 PM FRANK CALLED BACK TO REPORT A HAZARDOUS SPILL.  I IMMEDIATELY CALLED FORT SMITH SAFETY AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT.  I CALLED SPECTRUM CHEMICAL TO SEE OF THEY COULD HELP ON THE CLEAN UP.  I THEN HAD THE GENERAL OFFICE TALK TO SPECTRUM CHEMICAL PERSONNALLY.  SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY AM PUMPING. INSTRUCTIONS FOR PROPER FREIGHT HANDLING WILL BE GIVEN TO DRIVER.
column172: Glass container, no capacity or description given

column168: DISPATCHER FAILED TO COLLECT PROPER INFORMATION FOR OUR DRIVER TO DO A SUFFICIENT JOB.  CUSTOMER REQUESTED APPROPRIATE BOBTAIL UNIT ONLY FOR THIS PERTICULAR DELIVERY AND OUR DISPATCHER DISPATCHED THIS DELIVERY TO A DRIVER IN TRUCK AND TRAILER UNIT.  DRIVER DID READ DISPATCH SHEET AND BOBTAILED HIS TRUCK TO UCSD.  HE GOT TO THE SCENE HAD NO PROBLEM FUELING ABOVE THE GROUND TANK WITH HIS UNIT, BUT HIS JOB WAS NOT YET COMPLETE. THE CUSTOMER HAD A UTILITY TRAILER WITH  A SMALL GENERATOR INSIDE REQUESTED THAT DRIVER FUEL IT BEFORE HIS DEPARTURE.  DRIVER SAID, "HE TRYED TO EXPLAIN TO CUSTOMER HE DIDN'T HAVE PROPER EQUIPMENT TO FILL GENERATOR.  HE ALSO ASKED CUSTOMER TO MOVE THE TWO SMALL GENERATORS FROM IN FRONT OF TRAILER, CUSTOMER SAID, THEY COULDN'T WHILE THEY WERE IN USE.  I RECEIVED THE SAME EXACT STATEMENT FROM SEVERAL OTHER DRIVERS ON DUTY THIS DAY THAT THE DRIVER INVOLVED WITH INCIDENT, BEFORE HE REQUESTED PRESONNEL BRING EXTRA HOSE TO SITE.  THE DRIVER'S STATEMENT TO THE DISPATCHER OVER RADIO THIS DELIVERY NEEDS UNIT EQUIPPED WITH WET HOSE AND REEL AND DISPATCHERS COMMENT OVER RADIO WAS JUST DO THE BEST TO CAN AND HE SENT ANOTHER DRIVER OUT TO SITE WITH EXTRA HOSE.  DRIVER OR DISPATCHER NEVER EVEN THOUGHT TO TELL THE DRIVER DELIVERING EXTRA HOSE TO STAY AND ASSIST THE DRIVER ON THE SCENE.  DRIVER PRECEEDED TO PUMP FUEL INTO GENERATOR HE HAD NO PROBLEMS UNTIL THE GENERATOR GOT FULL.  THEN IT SPRAYED OUT SOME FOAM AND APPROXIMATELY FIVE TO SEVEN GALLONS BUT IT'S VERY DOUBTFUL IT WAS THAT MUCH.  THERE JUST WASN'T ANYWAY POSSIBLE FOR THE DRIVER TO BE AT TWO PLACES AT THE SAME TIME, FOR EXAMPLE INSIDE TRAILER BY THE GENERATOR WHERE PRODUCT IS RELEASING AND AT UNIT BY PUMP CONTROLS TO MAKE SURE FLOW OF PRODCUT IS SHUT DOWN IMMEDIATELY.  THE DRIVER KNEW HIS CAPABILITIES BEFORE HE STARTED THIS DELIVERY.  AS YOU CAN SEE WE ALL NEED A FEW DAYS OF TRAINING.  WE CONTACTED OUR CUSTOMER AND REQUESTED TO HIM THAT ANYTIME THEY GET INFORMATION ON DELIVERY TO PLEASE ALWAYS TRY TO FIND OUT EXACTLY WHAT IS GOING TO FILL AT THE TIME OF DELIVERY, SPACE AVAILABILITY FOR OTHER UNITS, AND CAPACITY OF ALL TANKS.  WE HAVE CALLED A SAFETY MEETING FOR 10-15-91, TO GO OVER SITUATIONS SIMILAR TO THIS.  OTHER PROCEDURES IN LOADING AND UNLOADING UNITS.  COPIES OF SHIPPING PAPERS, ASSESSMENT REPORT PREPARED BY ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY ARE ATTACHED.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: (A).  EVENT THAT LED TO INCIDENT FROM COMPANY INVESTIGATION:  EMPLOYEE WAS ENDING HIS UNLOADING PROCEDURES BY WALKING OUT HOSES, MAKING SURE NO PRODUCT WAS LEFT IN HOSE BEFORE DISCONNECTION.  EMPLOYEE WHEN DOING THIS CLOSED INTERNAL & BETTS VALVE, BY HIM DOING THIS THERE WASN'T PROPER AIR SUPPLY TO PUSH PRODUCT CLEAR FROM HOSE.  WHEN HE DISCONNECTED HOSE FORM FILL PRODUCT BEGAN TO RELEASE THREE TO FIVE GALLONS OF LEADED REGULAR, GASOLINE.  FILL AREA HAD SLIGHT GRADE CAUSING PRODUCT TO SPREAD QUICKLY. (B).  ACTION TAKEN:  RECEIVED CALL ON SPILL, I WAS UNABLE TO LEAVE OFFICE RIGHT AWAY.  I CONNECTED OUR ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY TO RESPOND FOR SITE ASSEMENT, TAKE PHOTOGRAPHS, AND COMPLETE WRITTEN REPORT.  (C).  ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS:  GAVE EMPLOYEE VERBAL, WRITTEN & DEMONSTRATED TO HIM, CAREFUL AND CORRECT PROCEDURES TO TAKE IN FUTURE.  WE HAVE CALLED SAFETY MEETING, 10/15/90, SO TRAILER CAN GO OVER PROCEDURES WITH ALL EMPLOYEES.

(A).  WHAT CAUSED INCIDENT?  AFTER DRIVER HAD PUMPED THREE QUARTERS OF HIS LOAD POSSIBLY MORE INTO TANKS AT CUSTOMERS REQUEST, HE CLIMBED ON THE TOP OF THE TANK TO SEE HOW MUCH CAPACITY WAS LEFT.  DRIVRE SEEN THAT THE TANK COULD HOLD APPROXIMATELY FIFTEEN MORE INCHES OF PRODUCT.  THE DRIVER KNEW GOING BY TANK CHARTS THIS SIZE TANK WOULD HOLD THE REST OF HIS PRODUCT, SO HE PROCEEDED TO PUMING THE REMAINING GALLONS FROM HIS TRAILER, HE WALKED AWAY FROM FOR A SECOND AND OVERFILLED THE CUSTOMERS TANK, PERSONNEL ON SITE YELLED FOR HIM TO SHUT PUMP OFF.  DRIVER BEGAIN USING ABSORBENT PADS FROM SPILL KIT TO ABSORB FUEL FROM GROUND, PERSONNEL TOLD HIM NOT TO WORRY HTIS WASN'T FIRST INCIDENT.  PERSONNEL SAID TANK WASN'T LEVEL PARTIAL REASON FOR SPILL.  (B).  WE HAVE CALLED A SAFETY MEETING FOR ALL DRIVERS. TOPIC FOR MEETING PROPER PROCEDURES IN PUMPING PRODUCT ON UNIT AND OFF OF UNIT SAFELY.  FIRST RULE NEVER WALK AWAY FROM EQUIPMENT WHILE IN USE. (C). COPIES ATTACHED:  SHIPPING PAPERS AND DRIVER'S WRITTEN STATEMENT.  (D). CUSTOMER IS GOING TO TAKE CARE OF ALL CLEAN UP OF SPILL ALSO AGREED TO TAKE CARE OF HIS FAULTY EQUIPMENT ON SITE FOR FUTRE DELIVERIES.

COASTAL TRANSPORT DRIVER RUSSELL BROWN MADE A ROUTINE DELIVERY OF DIESEL FUEL TO THE CIRCLE B CONVENIENT STORE TO A 12,000 UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK WITH A 4 INCH TIGHTFILL CONNECTION FOR UNLOADING THE TRANSPORT TANK TRAILER BY A 4 INCH HOSE.  THE INCIDENT OCCURRED WHEN THE DIESEL FUEL FOAMED INSIDE THE STORAGE TANK CAUSING THE OVERFILL VALE TO CUT OFF THE FLOW OF FUEL AND SUBSEQUENTLY THE 4 INCH TIGHTFILL ADAPTOR PARTIALLU SEPARATED FROM THE 4 INCH TIGHTFILL HOSE CAUSING APPROX. 10 GALLONS TO SPILL ON THE CONCRETE DRIVEWAY.  THE ACTION TAKEN AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT WAS IMMDIATE CLEAN UP FILL OF THE DIESEL FUEL ON THE CONCRETE AND ON THE NEXT DAY ALL OF THE DIRT THAT WAS OR COULD HAVE POSSIBLY BEEN CONTAMINATED WITH THE DIESEL FUEL WAS REMOVED, PROPERLY DISPOSED AND NEW CLEAN FILL DIRT REPLACED IN THE HOLE.  THIS INCIDENT DID NOT RESULT IN ENVIRONMENTAL IMPAIRMENT AFTER IT WAS PROPERLY CLEANED UP.  OUR RECOMMENDATION TO PREVENT FUTURE SUCH INCIDENTS IS TO BE VERY CAREFUL WHEN CONNECTING THE FIGHTFILL HOSE ADAPTOR (FEMALE) TO THE 4 INCH RISER TIGHTFILL ADAPTOR (MALE).  THESE COUPLINGS MUST BE PROPERLY POSITIONED AND CONNECTED SO THAT THEY WILL NOT BE UNCOUPLED FROM THE FORCE THAT IS CREATED WHEN THE OVERFILL VALVE CAUSES THE FLOW OF DIESEL FUEL TO CEASE FLOWING INSTANTANEOUSLY WHEN THE VALVE CLOSES.
DURING UNLOADING, DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY DRUM ATTACHMENT ON FORKLIFT.  HOLE WAS PATCHED TO SEAL AND FORWARDED TO CONSIGNEE.  SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED WITH FLOOR DRY AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

column168: A TANKCAR ON OUTBOUND TRAIN M900 WAS ABSERVED BY CREW - A HAVING NOISE COMING FROM TOP OF TANKCAR.  SHIPPER CONTACTED, BUT UNABLE TO HAVE TEAM AT YARD FOR 6-8 HOURS.  T'MASTER MOORE CALLED LOCAL GAS COMPANY (AMERICAS) AND ARRANGED FOR MUTUAL ASSISTANCE.  AMIGAS EMPLOYEE JOHN BLACKWELL CAME TO YARD AND INSPECTED DOME OF TANKCAR.  THE LIQUID LINE VALVE WAS PARTIALLY OPEN, AND THE PLUG WAS NOT COMPLETELY TIGHT.  BLACKWELL CLOSED THE VALVE, PLACED TEFLON TAPE ON PLUG THREADS.  TIGHTENED PLUG INTO PLACED AND STOPPED LEAK.

AT 1:30 PM ON SEPTEMBER 30, 1991, 1 WAS NOTIFIED BY A BAXTER HEALTHCARE DRIVER THAT A SPILL OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID AND ACCURRED WHILE MAKING HIS DELIVERIES.  THIS SPILL OCCURRED AT THE RECEIVING DOCK OF THE SOUTH CAROLINA DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENTAL CONTROL, 8231 PARKLANE ROAD, COLUMBIA, SOUTH CAROLINA APPROXIMATE TIME OF THE SPILL WAS 12:30 PM. THIS SPILL WAS CONTAINED ON OUR PRIVATE TRUCK AND SPILL RESPONSE WAS MADE BY THE CHEMICAL SPILL TEAM ONN SITE AT DHEC.  THE COURSE OF ACTION TAKEN TO ADDRESS THIS SPILL WAS TO DECONTAMINATE THE TRAILER AND AFFECTED PALLET WITH A NEUTRALIZER.  GIVEN UNKNOWN CIRCUMSTANCES, AS TO WHY THE CONTAINER FAILED, PREVENTIVE ACTION OTHER THAN RESTATING PROPER CHEMICAL HANDLING TECHNIQUES IS NOT POSSIBLE.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER OF THE PETROLEUM WORLD TANKWAGON WAS TOP-LOADING AT THE SPARTAN PETROLEUM BULK PLANT WHEN A MOTOR OIL CUSTOMER CAME IN TO PICK UP AN ORDER.  THE WAREHOUSE DRIVERS AND MANAGER WERE ALL OUT MAKING DELIVERIES SO THE PETROLEUM WORLD DRIVER ASK TO HELP THE CUSTOMER.  HE TURNED OFF THE PUMP TO THE LOADING RACK IN ORDER TO LEAVE HIS TRUCK TO HELP THE CUSTOMER; HOWEVER, HE FORGOT TO CLOSE THE VALVE TO THE TANK FROM WHICH THE GAS WAS BEING PUMPED OUT OF INTO HIS TRUCK.  THE TANK BEING AN ABOVE GROUND TANK CAUSED THE PRODUCT TO BE PUSHED THROUGH THE LOADING ARM INTO THE TRUCK DUE TO GRAVITY.  WHEN THE DRIVER RETURNED APPROXIMATELY 380 GALLONS OF UNLEADED GASOLINE HAD RUN OVER THE SIDE OF THE TRUCK ACROSS THE ASPHALT AND APPROXIMATELY 50 YARDS ACROSS THE GRAVEL LOT.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY GOT A SHOVEL AND CONSTRUCTED A DIKE TO STOP AND CONTAIN THE SPILL.  HE THEN SOAKED ANY PRODUCT ON TOP OF THE GROUND WITH ABSORBANT PADS, PILLOWS AND BOOMS. THE INCIDENT OCCURRED AT 1500 HOURS AND BY 1630 THE CONTAMINATED SOIL HAD BEGAN TO BE REMOVED.  ALL THE CONTAMINATED AREA WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH FRESH DIRT AND APPROVED BY THE PROPER AUTHORITIES.  THE DRIVER HAS BEEN PUT ON PROBATION, RETRAINING AND HAS BEEN INSTRUCTED NOT TO EVER LEAVE HIS TRUCK WHILE LOADING OR UNLOADING.  HE HAS BEEN INSTRUCTED TO COMPLETE HIS TASK FULLY BEFORE HELPING A CUSTOMER OR ANYONE ELSE.

DRIVER WAS UNLOADING INTO DRUMS WHEN HOSE RUPTURED.  PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP IMMEDIATELY WITH ABSORBENTS.  APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED.

#1 REMOVING ELBOW THAT CONNECTS REAR VALVE OF TRAILER.  VERY SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPLASHED OUT OF ELBOW ONTO GROUND.

EM SCIENCE SHIPPED A MULTIPLE STOP SHIPMENT WHICH HAD PRODUCT DOUBLE STACKED IN THE NOSE OF TRAILER.  OUR INVESTIGATION INDICATES THAT SOMETIME BETWEEN THE SECOND AND THIRD DELIVERY THAT THE LOAD LOCK FELL AND 3 CARTONS OF XYLENE FELL TO THE FLOOR BREAKING SOME OF THE BOTTLES.  WHEN THE DRIVER OPENED TRAILER DOORS HE DISCOVERED THE OVERTURNED CARTONS, HE THEN PROCEEDED TO UPRIGHT THE THREE CARTONS TO PREVENT ADDITIONAL SPILLAGE.  OLIN HUNT CALLED IN A RESPONSE TEAM FROM OLIN HUNT MATERIALS TO PERFORM CLEAN-UP IN THE TRAILER.  DRIVER WAS EXAMINED AT THE MEDICAL CENTER AND RELEASED IMMEDIATELY.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER INCIDENTS EM SCIENCE WILL NOT SHIP ANY PRODUCTS DOUBLE DECKED.  CARRIER IS PREPARING HAZARDOUS BRIEFING TO BE READ AT TIME OF DISPATCH OF ANY HAZARDOUS LOAD TO INSURE THAT DRIVER WILL BE ROUTINELY REMINDED OF REGULATIONS AND RESPONSIBLE CARE.

THE WHEEL CHOCKS WERE REMOVED WHILE THE CAR WAS CONNECTED TO THE LOAD LINES AT THE LOADING PLATFORM.  THE CAR ROLLED SOUTHWARD APPROXIMATELY 10 FEET. THE VAPOR LINE PULLED OUT OF A THREADED ELBOW IN THE LOADING LINE ALLOWING AMMONIA VAPOR TO ESCAPE INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.  AN EMPLOYEE DONNED A SELF CONTAINED BREATHING APPARATUS, CLIMBED TO THE TOP OF THE CAR AND CLOSED THE VAPOR VALVE, STOPPING THE FLOW OF AMMONIA VAPOR.
CAR WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN YARD. CAR WAS ISOLATED.  SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR REPAIR.  BOTTOM OUTLET CAP TIGHTENED AND CAR SECURED.  SPILLED TO PRODUCT EVAPORATED.
CAR WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM RUPTURE DISK.  CSX PERSONNEL REPLACED DISC AND SECURED CAR.

column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING WEST ON RT 2 AND WAS NEALRY [ADT THE JCTO OF RT. 78 WHEN OUT TRAILER WAS STRUCK BY A FORD ESCORT THAT FAILED TO STOP FOR A BLINKING RED LIGHT AND STOP SIGN.  HE RAMMED INTO THE SIDE OF OUR TRAILER PUSHING THE METER BOX TO THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE TRAILER CAUSING THE INTERNALS TO OPEN ALLOWING THE FLOW OF PRODUCT WHICH BURST INTO FALMES AND CAUSED AND EXPLOSION.  THE HEAT CAUSED THE FUSIBLE LINKS TO MELT WHICH SHUT DOWN THE INTERNALS AND HELPED TO RETARD THE FIRE.  THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE BOTH A TOTAL LOSS AS WAS THE ESCORT.  THE MAN IN THE ESCORT WAS THOUGHT EO HAVE DIED FOR FROM THE COLLISION BUT WAS BURNED BEYOND IMMEDIATE RECOGNITION.  IT TOOK A COUPLE OF DAYS FOR IDENTIFICATION OF THE BODY.  THE EQUIPMENT WORKED AS IT WAS DESIGNED TO AND PREVENT THE SITUATION FROM BEING A GREATER DISASTER.

column168: THE PRODUCT BEING SHIPPED INITIALLY BEGAN SIMPLY, "LEAD FLAKE", AND WAS THEN ACCIDENTLY CONTAMINATED WITH A CORROSIVE, LOW PH SOLUTION OF CUS04 (COOPER SULFATE) PRIOR TO SHIPMENT.  IN ADDITION, THE CONTAINERS WERE DAMAGED BY THE SHIPPER DURING LOADING ON SEPTEMBER 26, 1991, AND WERE NOT DETECTABLE AT THE TIME.  THE SHIPMENT WAS NOTED LEAKING ON SEPTEMBER 27, 1991, AT APPROXIMATELY 1500 MST AND WAS THEN MOVED TO THE 4K TRUCKSTOP, EXIT 278 OFF INTERSTATE 10, NEAR THE CITY OF SAN SIMON, AZ.  A PLASTIC PAIL WAS THEN PLACED UNDER THE TRAILER AT THE LOCATION OF THE LEAK.  THE DRIVER THEN NOTIFIED THE ARIZONA DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY AND THE SHIPPER WAS THEN NOTIFIED BY OUR COMPANY SAFETY SUPERVISOR.  THE SHIPPER THEN MOBILIZED A LICENSED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, SOUTHWEST HAZARD CONTROL OUT OF TUCSON, AZ.  THE CONTRACTOR THEN SET UP A ZONE OF CONTROL, CONTAINED ANY FURTHER SPILLAGE, REMOVED AND OVERPACKED ALL THE DRUMS AND DECONTAMINATED THE TRAILER AND PAVEMENT IN THE CONTROL ZONE.  ALL SPILLED MATERIALS AND OTHER MATERIALS RESULTING FROM THE CLEAN UP WERE PROPERLY DISPOSED BY THE CONTRACTOR.  ALL OVERPACKED DRUMS WERE LOADED ON TO ANOTHER TRAILER AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE DAMAGED TRAILER WAS SENT TO A QUALIFIED REPAIR FACILITY TO DETERMINE IF ANY STRUCTURAL DAMAGE HAD RESULTED.  LESS THAT 2 GALLONS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS SPILLED, THUS NOT MAKING THIS A REPORTABLE QUANTITY INCIDENT AS DETERMINED BY THE SHIPPER AND CONTRACTOR.  AS A PRECAUTION, THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND THE AZ DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY OF A "POSSIBLE RQ SPILL" WITHIN THE 24 HOUR REPORTING PERIOD.  THE SHIPPER HAS MADE US AWARE THAT THEY ARE PRESENTLY RE-EVALUATING PACKING AND SHIPPING PROCEDURES IN ORDER TO ELIMINATE THE POSSIBILITY OF ANY FUTURE INCIDENTS.  FOR THE RECORD, THE DAMAGED TRAILER WAS INSPECTED AND AFTER MINOR REPAIR WAS DEEMED STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

TANK CAR NUMBER GATX 92719 LOADED WITH ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAS SET OUT ON INTERCHANGE TRACK AT CARTHAGE FOR MOVEMENT BY UNION PACIFIC TO ATLAS POWDER IN ATLAS, MISSOURI.  A NEARBY RESIDENT OBSERVED VAPOR PLUME FROM THE DOME AREA OF THE TANK CAR.  THIS WAS REPORTED TO THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED THE TRAIN DISPATCHER.  RESPONSE CAME FROM NEARBY CONSIGNEE ATLAS POWDER AND A BURLINGTON NORTHERN RAILROAD HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER.  THE ANHYDRUS AMMONIA WAS LEAKING FROM THE SAMPLE TUBE DUE TO AN INCOMPLETELY CLOSED SAMPLE TUBE VALVE AND AN INCOMPLETELY TIGHTENED SAMPLE TUBE PLUG.  THESE FITTINGS WERE SECURED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

column168: US FUEL OIL TRUCK WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON RT 295 AT A SPEED OF 50 MPH.  THE RIGHT FRONT SPRING BROKE CAUSING THE TRUCK TO ROLLOVER.  THE TRUCK STRUCK APPROX. 250 YARDS OF GUARD RAIL AND THEN ROLLED DOWN AN INCLINE IMPACTING A LARGE ROCK CAUSING THE REAR BULKHEAD TO RUPTURE.  FIRE AND RESCUE UNITS WERE IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED TO THE AREA AS WELL AS A CLEANUP CREW WHICH CONTAINED THE SPILL.  THE BALANCE OF THE FUEL LEFT ON THE DAMAGED VEHICLE WAS OFFLOADED INTO US FUEL TRUCKS.  WHEN EMPTIED, A WRECKER WAS BROUGHT IN TO REMOVE THE TRUCK FROM THE SCENE.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS EAST BOUND ON I-20, AT MILE MARKER 45.5 IN MINDEN, LOUISIANA (WEBSTER PARISH) ON SEPTEMBER 26, 1991 CENTRAL STANDARD TIME. HE WAS IN ROUTE FROM RATTAN, OKLAHOMA TO EMELLE, ALABAMA ON THE LAST SEGMENT OF A TRIP ORIGINATING IN CONLEY, GEORGIA. INVESTIGATION OF INCIDENT, INCLUDING ON-BOARD COMPUTER LOG AND SPEED READ-OUT, POINT TOWARD INDICATION THAT DRIVER EXPERIENCED ROAD HYPNOSIS AND CAUGHT THE LEFT SHOULDER OF ROADWAY.  DRIVER MAINTAINED UNIT IN A STRAIGHT AHEAD MOVEMENT SLOWING DOWN UNTIL UNIT CAME INTO CONTACT WITH GUARD RAILS. UNIT CONTINUED ON UNTIL ALMOST TOTALLY BACK ON ROADWAY AT WHICH POINT TRAILER TURNED ONTO ITS LEFT SIDE WHILE TRACTOR STAYED UPRIGHT. AFTER INSPECTING TRACTOR AND TRAILER FOR ANY LIQUID LEAKS AND FINDING NONE, DRIVER OBTAINED HELP AND NOTIFIED LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AND LOUISIANA STATE POLICE T.E.S.S. - HAZMAT UNIT., STATE OF LOUISIANA, DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, OFFICE OF HAZARDOUS WASTE/EMERGENCY RESPONSE WERE ALSO NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO SCENE.  UPON INSPECTION OF LOAD OF 73 DRUMS, ONE WAS NOTED TO HAVE OPENED DUE TO ACCIDENT, 16 MORE WERE SLIGHTLY DAMAGED BUT DID NOT OPEN.  JONES BROS ENVIRONMENTAL, BOSSIER CITY, LOUISIANA WAS NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED EQUIPMENT TO THE SCENE FOR CLEAN-UP OPERATION.  STEVE SHIELDS AND STEVE HOFFMAN, HICKSON PERSONNEL, WERE ALSO SENT TO SCENE TO HELP WITH CLEAN-UP PROCEDURES. ALL DRUMS WERE REMOVED FROM TRAILER AND MOVED BY JONES BROS TO THEIR TERMINAL AT BOSSIER CITY TO AWAIT FURTHER TRANSPORTATION BY ALLWASTE SYSTEMS OF ATLANTA TO EMELLE, ALABAMA FOR DISPOSAL.  THE ONE OPENED DRUM AND THE 16 DAMAGED WERE PUT INTO OVERPACK DRUMS AND SEALED BEFORE TRANSPORTATION TO EMELLE.  DURING CLEAN-UP OF SITE, ONE EXTRA DRUM WAS GENERATED FROM THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND SURROUNDING DIRT MAKING A TOTAL OF 74 DRUMS TRANSPORTED TO EMELLE.  THE DRUM WAS MANIFESTED FOR SHIPMENT TO EMELLE BY THE STATE OF LOUISIANA, DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, OFFICE OF HAZARDOUS WASTE/EMERGENCY UNIT.  SOIL SAMPLES WERE TAKEN FROM THE SPILL SITE AND ANALYTICAL RESULTS FROM LAW AND COMPANY SHOW THAT CLEAN-UP WAS SUCCESSFUL. THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE TAKEN BY HALL'S WRECKER SERVICE TO THEIR HOLDING YARD AND LATER TRANSPORTED TO REPAIR FACILITIES.  JONES BROS ENVIRONMENTAL ALSO REPAIRED SURROUNDING AREA OF ACCIDENT SITE TO LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION REQUIREMENTS.  GUARD RAILS WERE REPAIRED BY MADDEN CONTRACTING COMPANY TO LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION REQUIREMENTS. HICKSON CORPORATIONS'S DEPARTMENT OF SAFETY, HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENTAL IN CONJUNTION WITH THE TRAFFIC DEPARTMENT ARE OBTAINING INFORMATION AND FILMS, TO INCORPORATE INTO OUR ALREADY ON-GOING DRIVER SAFETY PROGRAM, TO AID IN RECOGNIZING AND COMBATTING THIS TYPE OF DRIVER HAZARD. DRIVER SAFETY MEETINGS ARE AND WILL CONTINUE TO BE HELD PROMOTING DRIVE AWARENESS TO ALL TYPES OF DRIVING HAZARDS AND ACTIONS THAT NEED TO BE TAKEN TO AVOID THEM.  OUR TRAFFIC DEPARTMENT IS ALSO EXPLORING TRAILER MODIFICATIONS THAT W

column168: WHEN THE COURIER SET THE PACKAGE ON THE FLOOR THE BOTTOMS OF THE INNER PACKAGING BROKE.  HE DID NOT KNOW THIS BOX WAS LEAKING UNTIL HE WALKED BACK OVER TO WHERE HE SAT IT DOWN.  HE SAID LIQUID STARTED COMING OUT OF THE BOTTOM.  ANOTHER EMPLOYEE NOTIFIED A MANAGER.  THE MANAGER INFORMED THE COURIERS IN THE AREA TO KEEP A SAFE DISTANCE FROM THE LIQUID.  THE MANAGER CALLED THE 800 NUMBER ON THE AIRBILL TO GET INSTRUCTIONS ON HOW TO CLEANUP THE SPILL.  THE MANAGER ALSO TALKED WITH THE RESTRICTED ARTICLES DEPARTEMNT OF FEDERAL EXPRESS.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND ALL MATERIALS USED FOR THE CLEANUP PLUS THE REMAINING GOOD PRODUCT WAS DELIVERED TO MCCORMICK (THE RECIPIENT).  MY ONLY SUGGESTION FOR IMPROVING THE PACKAGING IS NOT TO PACK THIS LIQUID IN GLASS.  IT IS QUESTIONABLE WHETHER THIS PACKAGE WILL WITHSTAND A FOUR FOOT DROP TEST AS REQUIRED BY 173.6 IN TITLE 49.

DRIVER NOTICED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE CARGO TANK UPON RETURNING TO THE EQUIPMENT FOLLOWING A MEAL BREAK.  A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE LEAK TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT.  ANOTHER CARGO TANK WAS BROUGHT TO THE SCENE AND THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSLOADED FROM THE LEAKING TANK. APPROXIMATELY 7 GALLONS LEAKED FROM THE TIME THE LEAK WAS FIRST DISCOVERED UNTIL THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED.  SIX GALLONS WERE CONTAINED IN A BUCKET. THE OTHER GALLON LEAKED TO THE GROUND AND WAS CLEANED UP FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. LEAK WAS LATER DETERMINED TO HAVE BEEN COMING FROM A CRACKED WELD WHICH ATTACHED A CLEANOUT FITTING TO THE BOTTOM OF THE CARGO TANK.

THE CUSTOMER, ANCHOR GLASS, ORDERED 20 LOADS OF PRODUCT TO BE DELIVERED INTO A 200,000 GALLON STORAGE TANK.  19 LOADS WERE DELIVERED WITHOUT INCIDENT.  ON THE 20TH LOAD THE LAST 700 GALLONS OVER FLOWED THROUGH THE STORAGE TANK TOP VENT.  THIS TANK IS LOCATED IN A CEMENT BOTTOM AND CEMENT WALLED AREA.  THE CUSTOMER MISCALCULATED THE AUTOMATIC TANK GAUGE AS DID OUR DRIVER, CREATING THE OVERFLOW.  CUSTOMER WILL USE MANUAL GAUGE IN THE FUTURE.  ALL 700 GAL. OF PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED.  CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. WAS HIRED TO WASH THE AREA.  A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE STATE DEP SUPERVISED THE CLEANUP. ON OCTOBER 10, 1991 I BEGAN CALLING CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES ATTEMPTING TO LOCATE A MANIFEST TO FILE WITH THIS REPORT.  IT WAS NOT UNTIL THIS DATE 11-4-91 THAT I WAS INFORMED THAT THERE WOULD BE NO MANIFEST.  AS ALL PRODUCT AND CLEANING MATERIAL (#2 FUEL OIL) WAS RETURNED TO THE PRODUCT STORAGE TANK THE GLOVES AND BOOTS WORN BY THE CLEANING CREW WERE WASHED AND DECLARED REUSABLE.

column168: DRIVER STATED HE WAS TRAVELLING EAST ON STATE HIGHWAY 3 EAST OF THE CITY OF ATOKA, OK.  AS HE APPROACHED THE CREST IN THE LOAD, HE ABSERVED A WET-BOUND VEHICLE IN THE EAST-BOUND LANE PASSING ANOTHER VEHICLE.  HE PULLED HIS VEHICLE ONTO THE SHOULDER, AND LOST CONTROL BECAUSE THE SHOULDER WAS WET AND SOFT.  THIS CAUSED THE TRAILER TO TRACK TOWARD THE BARDITCH AND THE TRUCK AND THE TRAILER TO OVERTURN ONE AND 3/4 TIMES.  THE LEAK WAS CAUSED FROM A VERY SMALL RIP IN THE VENT RECOVERY PIPE.

column168: SHIFTED LOAD IN CONTAINER CTIU 172985 CAUSED THREE 5-GALLON DRUMS OF PRODUCT TO SPILL INSIDE OF CONTAINER.  MATERIAL EVAPORATED QUICKLY INTO ATMOSPHERE.  OLYMPUS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES DECONTAMINATED CONTAINER AND REPORTED FOR SHIPMENT.H

TRANSPORT SOUTH DRIVER FAILED TO PROPERLY CHECK HIS PUMPING EQUIPMENT BEFORE UNLOADING WHEREBY MALFUNCTIONED PUMPS SAFETY DEVICE WAS NOT IN PLACE CREATING A SPILLAGE.  CLEAN-UP WAS PERFORMED BY COMPANY PERSONNEL AND ABSORPTION PADS WERE DISPOSED OF BY CONTRACT.

DRIVER COMPLETED HOOK-UP TO CUSTOMER'S LINE AND BEGAN THE PUMPING PROCESS. AFTER SEVERAL MINUTES, HE NOTICED NO PRODUCT WAS BEING TRANSFERRED.  HE INCREASED PRESSURE TO THE OFF-LOADING LINE.  THE HOSE RUPTURED AT THE HOOK UP.  THE DRIVER HAD FAILED TO REMOVE A TEFLON BLANK GASKET ON THE CUSTOMER'S LINE AND WAS PUMPING AGAINST IT.  LEAK WAS DUE TO CARELESS HOOK-UP AND OVER PRESSURIZING THE LINE.

column168: PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED WITH LEAKAGE NOTED ON THE BOX.  EXAMINATION OF THE INNER CONTAINER REVEALED THAT THE CONTAINER(S) HAD LOOSE CAP(S) AND LEAKED. CARTON WAS WET BUT OTHERWISE UNDAMAGED.  PACKAGE WAS REPACKED FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.

column168: PACKAGE WAS DROPPED IN HANDLING.  EXAMINATION OF THE INNER CONTAINER REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON THE METAL CAN POPPED LOOSE AND LEAKED.  CARTON WAS WET BUT OTHERWISE UNDAMAGED.  CAP WAS REPLACED AND PACKAGE WAS REPACKED FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.

DRIVER UNLOADING INTO UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS, THE VENTS ON THE UNDERGROUND TANKS WERE RESTRICTED CAUSING A BUILDUP OF PRESSURE.  UPON REMOVAL OF UNLOADING HOSE A BLOWBACK OCCURED CAUSING PRODUCT TO SPILL ONTO PAVEMENT.  DRIVER CAPPED TANK AND SPREAD SAND ON SPILLED PRODUCT AND CLEANED UP.

WHILE OFFLOADING, 1 CONTAINER WAS RAMMED/PUNCTURED WITH A FORKLIFT ALLOWING MATERIAL TO SPILL ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE DRIVER FAILED TO INSPECT INSIDE OF TRAILER NOR REPORT ANY SIGN OF CONTAMINATION AFTER OFFLOADING.  THE CONTAMINATION WAS NOT DISCOVERED UNTIL 14 DAYS LATER ON OCTOBER 9, 1991 AT JOPLIN, MO WHERE THE TRAILER HAD SAT SINCE OFFLOADED AT GLOVER, MO ON SEPT. 25, 1991.  THE SPILLAGE WAS CONTAINED TO THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER WHICH WAS EQUIPPED WITH A STEEL SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAN THUS PREVENTING ANY RELEASE TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  THE FLOOR WAS CLEANED BY A LICENSED CLEAN-UP FACILITY.
WHEN PULLING HOSES OF TRUCK TO BEGIN TO UNLOAD, FUEL OIL RAN OUT OF HOSES ONTO GROUND.

CAR HAD A RUPTURED SAFETY VENT DISC.  DISC WAS REPLACED.  CAR WAS DECONTAMINATED BY DISPOSAL CONTROL SERVICES, 884 FREEPORT, SPARKS, NV.  3 DRUMS OF NEUTRALIZED MATERIAL AND CLOTHING WERE GENERATED AND WAS DISPOSED OF AT LOCKWOOD LANDFILL.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: 1430 HOURS:  RECEIVED A CALL FROM MR. CHARLES THOMAS, SP POLICE INTERMODAL CONTAINER TRANSFER FACILITY, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA, THAT CONTAINER, YMLU 260362, WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE CENTER AREA OF THE CONTAINER AT A RATE OF 10 DROPS PER MINUTE. WAYBILL REVEALED THAT THE CONTAINER WAS A MIXED LOAD OF PETROLEUM PRODUCTS WITH A STCC OF 4950120 CONTAINING: 10 DRUMS ISOPROPANOL 19 DRUMS ETANOL 20 BAGS HARMESS CHEMICAL 48 DRUMS HARMLESS CHEMICAL TOTAL: 97 PIECES 1440 HOURS:  CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL TRANSLOADING SERVICES, LOS ANGELES, AT 213-628-7000, TO TRANSLOAD THE CONTAINER AND OVERPACK LEAKING DRUMS WITH INSTRUCTIONS TO BILL THE SHIPPER DIRECT IF THE LOAD WAS NOT PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED. 1700 HOURS:  WAS ADVISED BY MR. THOMAS THAT THE LOAD WAS IMPROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED AND THAT ETS WAS IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSLOADING THE CONTAINER.  LEAKING DRUM HAD NOT BEEN IDENTIFIED AT THIS TIME. 2100 HOURS:  WAS ADVISED BY MR. DAVID BECKER OF ETS THAT THEY HAD FOUND THE LEAKING DRUM. IT WAS IDENTIFIED AS ETHYL ALCOHOL, DENATURED, AND IT WAS LEAKING FROM AROUND THE CHIME AREA OF THE DRUM WHERE IT APPEARED THAT THE DRUM WAS RUBBING AGAINST OTHER DRUMS.  APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.
CARBOY OF SULFURIC ACID FELL OFF OF A PALLET DURING UNLOADING.

column168: A SKID OF 5 GALLON PAILS GOING TO AQUA BLAST WAS STACKED ON TOP OF SIDE OF REELS.  THE SKID WAS NOT SUPPORTED PROPERLY CAUSING THE PAILS TO SLIDE OFF THE SKID AND TURN OVER.  ONE 5 GALLON PAIL LEAKED CONTENTS ONTO THE OTHER FREIGHT.  WHEN DISCOVERED, POLLUTION CONTROLS SYSTEMS WAS CALLED TO CLEAN UP AND DISPOSE OF EXPOSED MATERIALS.  CLEANUP COMPLETED ON SAME DAY AS SPILL.  SKID SHOULD HAVE BEEN LOADED ON FLOOR WITH PROPER DUNNAGE TO PREVENT TURNOVER.

column168: SEPT. 23, 1991, AT 7:45 PM, E.T.S DRIVER RAY DRIVER DISCOVERED ON HIS PRE-TRIP INSPECTION THAT HIS TRAILER CONTAINED A LEAKING DRUM.  AFTER THE TERMINAL MANAGER, ONE DRIVER AND TWO SHOP WORKERS UNLOADED ONE-THIRD OF THE LOAD, THEY DISCOVERED A 17C DRUM CONTAINING A MIXTURE OF WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID LEAKING AT THE BOTTOM OF THE SIDE SEAM.  AFTER OVERPACKING THE LEAKING DRUM AND CLEAN-UP MATERIAL, THE TRAILER WAS RELOADED AND SENT TO THE DISPOSAL FACILITY. NO MATERIAL WAS LEAKED INTO THE ENVIRONMENT.  ALL E.T.S VAN TRAILERS HAVE STEEL CONTAINMENT PANS INSIDE THAT ARE LIQUID PROOF.

WHILE AIR OFFLOADING THE PRODUCT FROM THE CARGO TANK, A CRACK DEVELOPED IN A VALVE LOCATED ON TOP OFF THE TANK.  AIR PRESSURE WAS SHUT OFF TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT.  BECAUSE OF THE LOCATION ON THE CRACK, CLOSING THE VALVE DID NOT STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT.  (PRODUCT STOPPED LEAKING FROM THE CRACK IN THE VALVE ONCE THE AIR PRESSURE BLED OFF THE TANK).  CARGO TANK WAS PLACED OUT OF SERVICE AND IS CURRENTLY AWAITING REPAIR ACTION. SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP FOR DISPOSAL BY PLANT PERSONNEL.

AGENT NOTICED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM BOTTOM VALVE OF CAR.  CALLED CONSIGNEE TO RAILROAD YARD TO INSPECT.  CALLED CHEMTREC AND REPORTED THE LEAK. CONSIGNEE TIGHTENED TOP VALVE AND DRIPPING STOPPED.  CONSIGNEE ADVISED AGENT NOT ENOUGH PRODUCT LOST TO INVOLVE REPORTING.  AGENT WAS UNAWARE ALL SPILLS MUST BE REPORTED REGARDLESS HOW SMALL.  HE NOW UNDERSTANDS.

FOUND LIQUID LINE PLUG LOOSE AND LEAKING BY VALVE THREADS, VALVE LEAKING THROUGH ALSO, SHIPPER HANDLED REPAIRS AND TANK CAR PROCEEDED TO DESTINATION.

PASSENGER THOMAS TURNER PACKED A BOX OF STRIKE ANY WHERE MATCHES IN HIS BACK PACK.  PASSENGER TRAVELED ON ALASKA FLIGHTS 201/93 ON THE 6TH OF SEPTEMBER FROM PORTLAND, OR TO SEATTLE, WA TO ANCHORAGE, AK.  THE PACK PACK WAS ONLOADED FROM THE AIRCRAFT IN ANCHORAGE AND WHILE IT WAS BEING PLACED IN THE BAG CART, SMOKE STARTED COMING FROM ONE OF THE POCKETS. AFTER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A BOX OF STRIKE ANYWHERE MATCHES HAD IGNITED.  FAA SPECIAL AGENT JOHN WHITE WAS NOTIFIED AND CAME DIRECTLY TO THE AIRPORT.  THE PASSENGER WAS INTERVIEWED BY AST WHITE AND THE INVESTIGATION WAS TURNED OVER TO HIM.

column42: HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: ON SEPTEMBER 2, 1991, AROUND 11:20 A.M. OUR DRIVER, JOHN HAIZLIP LEFT FLORIDA STEEL CORPORATION, P.O. BOX 518, BALDWIN, FLORIDA 32234 HEADED TO HORSEHEAD RESOURCES DEVELOPMENT COMPANY, EAST PLANT, DELAWARE AVENUE, PLAMERTON, PA. 18071.  THE TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH RQ HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID N.O.S., ORM-E, NA9189 (EMISSION CONTROL DUST/SLUGE FROM THE PRIMARY PRODUCTION OF STEEL IN ELECTRIC FURNACE) (K061) (D006, D008) ERG. #31.  AS HE LEFT THE PLANT, WITHIN A THREE MILE AREA MR. HAIZLIP WENT OVER THREE SETS OF RAILROAD TRACKS (I90/301 SOUTH), AND EMISSION CONTROL DUST LEAKED OUT OF THE TAILGATE ONTO THE TRACKS AND ROADWAY.  MR.  HAIZLIP WAS NOT AWARE OF THE INCIDENT.  THE LAOD WAS DELIVERED WITH NO FURTHER PROBLEM. THE MATERIAL THAT LEAKED APPARENTLY WAS BETWEEN THE LINER AND THE TAILGATE.  THE LINER HELD CAUSING NO ADDITIONAL LOSS.  A RESIDENT OF BALDWIN WAS IN THE AREA, INFORMED THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES WHICH INFORMED FLORIDA STEEL OF THE SPILL.  FLORIDA STEEL CAME TO THE SCENE AND VACUUMED UP ABOUT 100 LBS. OF THE DUST.  FLORIDA STATE POLICE, CITY BALWIN POLICE, AND JACKSON CITY ENVIRONMENTAL WERE AT THE SCENE.
column172: Highway hopper trailer for solid materials only

column42: HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: ON SEPTEMBER 4, 1991, AROUND 10:00 AM OUR DRIVER, MR CHARLES MCGOWEN, TURNED UP THE HILL BY THE OFFICE AT THE ENTRANCE TO CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT, STAR ROUTE BOX 9, ARLINGTON, OR 97812.  WHEN CROSSING THE CATTLE GRATE, THE TAILGATE ON THE PULL-TRAILER POPPED OPEN, RELEASING A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID THAT HAD ACCUMULATED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER (APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GAL. 4 LBS.).  CHARLES CHECKED THE TAILGATE RELEASE SWITCH AND FOUND IT TO BE IN THE LOCKED POSITION, YET THE TAILGATE WAS OPEN.  SAFETY CHAINS HELD THE LOAD IN PLACE.  HE PULLED INTO THE STAGING AREA, DIAPERED THE DUMPED VEHICLE AND APPROXIMATELY ONE HOUR LATER WENT AHEAD AND DUMPED THE LOAD WITH NO FURTHER LEAKAGE. THE MATERIAL ON THE ROADWAY WAS CLEANED UP WITH A SCRAPER (SITE EQUIPMENT) AND DISPOSED OF IN THE LANDFILL. THE LOAD ORIGINATED FROM CHEVRON CANADA LIMITED, 355 N. WILLINGTON AVENUE, BURNABY, BC.  THE MATERIAL WAS RQ HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID, NOS ORM-E, NA9189, D009, PROFILE #J81578-PDX. NATIONAL RESPONSE AND THE OREGON DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, PENDELTON, OR 97801 WERE NOTIFIED.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0715 HOURS, FRIDAT\Y, SEPTEMBER 6, 1991, A YARDMASTER WORKING AT THE CONRAIL CONWAY, PA RAIL YARD OBSERVED PRODUCT MIST COMING FROM THE TOP VALVE AREA OF TANK CAR GATX-39382 (HYDROCHLORIC ACID) WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC, SHIPEPR AND THE BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES WERE NOTIFIED.  SENIOR INSPECTOR T. MANNAS OF THE AAR/BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES ARRIVED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CARS AT APPROXIMATELY 1015 HOURS, SEPTEMBER, 30TH, AND UPON INSPECTION FOUND A RUPTURED 100 POUN FRANGIBLE DISK IN THE CAR'S SAFETY VENT WHICH WAS ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE WHEN THE CAR MOVED.  THE RUPTURED DISK WAS REMOVED AND A NEW DISK WAS INSERTED INTO THE SAFETY VENT BY INSPECTOR MANNAS.  CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT 1045 HOURS, SEPTEMBER 6, 1991.

column18: P O BOX 619616 DFW INTL AIRPOT
column168: A PASSENGER AT CHECK-IN FAILED TO DECLARE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INSIDE HIS SUITCASE.  ON ARRIVAL OF HIS FLIGHT 437/2SEP DFWAMA IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A 1 GALLON CONTAINER OF TOILET BOWL CLEANER CONTAINING A HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION LEAKED OUT.  THE PLASTIC BOTTLE HAD A SMALL PUNCTURE AND LEAKED OUT INTO SUITCASE AND THROUGH THE SUITCASE ON TO OTHER PASSENGER BAGS AND THE BELLY OF THE AIRCRAFT.  THE BAGGAGE HANDLERS WHO WERE WORKING INSIDE THE BELLY AND OUTSIDE THE RAMP WERE SENT TO THE HOSPITAL AS A PRECAUTION. THEY WERE RELEASED SHORTLY AFTERWARDS.  THE AMARILLO FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZ MAT TEAM CLEANED UP THE SPILL.  CONTRACT AIRCRAFT MAINTENANCE INSPECTED BELLY AND NO DAMAGE WAS FOUND TO AIRCRAFT.  APPROXIMATELY 20 OTHER SUITCASES AND CONTENTS WERE DAMAGED.   DISPATCH, SYSTEM OPERATIONS CONTROL AND FAA WERE ALL NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.
column172: Plastic bottle, capacity 2 gallons or less

column168: NOTE: THERE WAS NO SPILLAGE OR DAMAGE TO CARGO WHATSOEVER. COMPANY DRIVER ROBERT SCOTT WAS NORTHBOUND I-95, NEAR RIDGELAND, S.C. MILE MARKER 15.9 WHEN HE ATTEMPTED TO PASS ANOTHER TRUCK-TRAILER.  THE DRIVER OF OTHER VEHICLE SWERVED INTO THE LEFT LANE CAUSING TO VEER TO THE LEFT UNTO THE GRASS OF MEDIUM STRIP TO AVOID A COLLISION WITH OTHER VEHICLE. OUR DRIVER APPLIED HIS BRAKES, BUT THE WEIGHT OF LOAD AND WET GRASS FAILED TO STOP UNIT BEFORE REACHING THE WOODED AREA OF THE MEDIUM.  IN THE PROCESS OF CLEARING THE AREA OF ACCIDENT, I-95 WAS CLOSED TO TRAFFIC, FOR ABOUT TWO HOURS, TO AVOID ANY DANGER TO THE PUBLIC, IN THE EVENT OF ANY FURTHER DAMAGE THAT COULD OCCUR IN THE PROCESS OF CLEARING THE SCENE OF ACCIDENT.  WHILE AWAITING THE ARRIVAL OF THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM FROM MONSANTO CHEMICAL CO, WE HAD SEVERAL FIRE DEPARTMENTS FROM THE SURROUNDING AREAS THERE AT THE SCENE.  UPON ARRIVAL OF MONSANTO RESPONSE TEAM, THEY INSPECTED THE ACCIDENT AND SUGGESTED THAT IT BE MOVED TO SAFE HAVEN ON GODBEE YARD.

SFTU ARRIVED CORWITH YARD 9-6-91 AT 1300 ON SLACHI-03, LEAKING A HAZARDOUS LIQUID. LOAD CONSISTED OF 74 55 GAL STEEL DRUMS OF RESIN SOLUTION, FLAMMABLE, UN1866.  TRAILER WAS PLACED IN OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SAFETY HAVEN.  MR. MIKE CARTER OF HUB CITY, LOS ANGELES, TERMINAL INC., WAS CONTACTED HE ADVISED SHIPMENT WAS DESTINED REICHHOLD CHEMICALS, BRIDGEVILLE, PA., VIA HIGHWAY BY TRITON TRANSPORT SERVICES, I INFORMED CARTER ONE DRUM WAS LEAKING DUE TO METAL FATIGUE OF BOTTOM ROLLING HOOP. CAUSED BY CONTINUOUS RUBBING WITH ADJACENT DRUM.  AT THE EXPENSE OF MR. CARTER DRUMS WERE LOADED INTO SFVZ 732379 BY ROGERS TRANSFER. LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM.  SAND ABSORBING LIQUID RESIN WAS PUT ON A PLSTIC BAG AND ALSO LOADED INTO SFVZ 732379 BY ROGERS TRANSFER.  LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM FOR RESICHOLD CHEMICAL DISPOSAL. APROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS ESCAPED FROM DRUM.  SFVZ 768045 WAS STEAM CLEANED AT CORWITH YARD.  SFVZ 732379 DEPARTED CORWITH PIGGYBACK YARD 9-7-91.

OUR DRIVER DELIVERED A LOAD (7100 GAL.) OF #2 DIESEL FUEL TO PENSKE TRUCK LEASING IN PARAGOULD, ARK.  ON ARRIVAL OUR DRIVER NOTIFIED A MR. ROBERT BROADWATER (SUPERVISOR AT PENSKE) THAT HE HAD 7100 GALS. OF DIESEL FUEL, MR. BROADWATER INSTRUCTED OUR DRIVER TO PUMP THE FUEL INTO THE STORAGE TANK.  OUR DRIVER WAS UNLOADING THE FUEL AND HAD UNLOADED 6064 GAL. WHEN THE TANK STARTED TO OVERFLOW SPILLING APPROX 77. GAL.  PENSKE HAD MISTAKINGLY ORDERED MORE FUEL THAN THEIR TANK WOULD HOLD AT THIS TIME. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION WE FOUND A DEFECTIVE TANK GAUGE.  THE TANK GAUGE WAS STUCK AND SHOWING AN INCORRECT READING.  WE REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO THE OFFICE OF HAZARDOUS MAT. IN ATLANTA, GA. AND THE CLEANUP IS BEING DONE BY CTC INDUSTRIAL SERVICES, 1827 LATHAM ST. MEMPHIS TN. (901) 942-1212.

column168: CALZONA TANKWAYS DRIVER JON ZIEMBA FAILED TO PROPERLY PARK HIS TRUCK AT STATION 98573.  JON ZIEMBA PARKED THE TRUCK USING TROLLEY BRAKE (TRAILER ONLY LEVER BRAKE) INSTEAD OF SPRING PARKING BRAKE.  AFTER HOOKING PRODUCT HOSE TO UNLEADED TANK FILL AMD TO COMPARTMENT #1 OF TRUCK, JON STARTED FLOW OF PRODUCT THEN LEFT TRUCK UNATTENDED AND WALKED AROUND TO FRONT OF STATION TO PICKUP PAYMENT.  WHEN JON RETURNED, TRUCK WAS ROLLING BACKWARDS AND OUT INTO STREET EDGE TAKING SLACK OUT OF PRODUCT UNLOADING HOSE, BREAKING PIPING AT TRUCK UNLOADING HEADER WHICH ALLOWED APPROXIMATELY 300 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO SPILL ONTO STATION PAVEMENT.  PRODUCT TRAVELED IN TWO DIRECTIONS,  APPROXIMATELY 250' AND INTO TWO STROM DRAINS WHICH WERE CONNECTED.  CORONA POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS WERE CALLED AND FIRE DEPARTMENT DIKED BOTH STORM DRAIN AND USED A SMALL AMOUNT OF ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  ONLY A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ENTERED STORM DRAINS, REMAINDER OF PRODUCT EVAPORATED.  INCIDENT WAS COVERED AT SAFETY MEETING ON 09/12/91 TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE.

DRIVER/SALESMAN WAS UNLOADING THE DRUM WHEN IT SLIPPED OFF THE BARREL WHEELER.  THE DRUM FELL TO THE FLOOR, STRIKING THE PRONGS OF THE DOLLY, PUNCTURING THE SIDEWALL OF THE DRUM.  JOHN GRAMMER OF TEXO CORP. WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE SITUATION.  MR.  GRAMMER ADVISED, AND WE FOLLOWED HIS INSTRUCTIONS, ON THE CLEANUP AND DISPOSAL OF THE MATERIAL.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Corrosion - Exterior
column168: ON MONDAY, SEPTEMBER 16, 1991, AT APPROXIMATELY 2000 HOURS, TANK CAR GATX 85269 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM NOTIFIED THE ON-DUTY TRANSPORTATION SUPERVISOR, DAVE THELEN, WHO WENT TO THE NO. 6 TRACK IN ACCA SOUTH YARD TO INSPECT THE TANK CAR.  MR. THELEN FOUND A STEADY LEAK COMING OUT OF A 2 INCH PIPE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR AT 2015 HOURS. AT 2030 HOURS MR. T.W. GRUBBS, RF&P'S SUPERVISOR POLICE AND SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY MR. THELEN OF THE LEAK, AND RESPONDED TO ACCA YARD ARRIVING APPROXIMATELY 2120 HOURS.  AN INSPECTION WAS MADE OF THE TANK CAR AT 2140 HOURS AND THE LEAK WAS FOUND TO BE COMING FROM ONE OF THE STEAM HEATER COIL PIPES, LOCATED ON EITHER SIDE OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  NEITHER OF THE HEATER COIL PIPES AND THE CAPS SECURED; BOTH WERE DANGLING FROM THEIR CHAINS.  BOTH CAPS WERE TIGHTLY SCREWED ONTO THE PIPING AND THIS STOPPED THE LEAK AT 2230 HOURS.  NO PONDING OR GROUND ACCUMULATION WAS EVIDENT. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AT 2315 HOURS AND THEY, IN TURN, NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, WESTVACO CORPORATION.  AT 2335 HOURS MR. CHARLES W. MIZZELL, TRANSPORTATION AND DISTRIBUTION MANAGER OF WESTVACO, P O BOX 70848, CHARLESTON HEIGHTS, SOUTH CAROLINA, CALLED AND WAS ADVISED THE WASTE LIQUOR WAS ENTERING THE HEATER COIL PIPING.  MR.  MIZZELL ADVISED ONCE THE CAR WOULD BE UNLOADED AND THEN SHOPPED FOR REPAIRS.  THE TANK CAR WAS INSPECTED AGAIN AT 0030 HOURS ON TUESDAY, SEPTEMBER 17, 1991, AND FOUND NOT TO BE LEAKING AND WAS PUT BACK ONTO RAIL AND SERVICE AT THAT TIME. TANK CAR DEPARTED ACCA YARD AT 0325 HOURS SEPTEMBER 17, 1991, ON CSXT TRAIN NO. 30117.   THE TANK CAR WAS SHIPPED FROM THE WESTVACO PLANT IN LUKE, MARYLAND.

column168: A KEROSENE LAMP USED FOR CAMPING STILL CONTAINING SOME KEROSENE WAS CARRIED ON BOARD SOUTHWEST AIRLINES FLIGHT #888.  POSSIBLY DUE TO LEANING OR SHIFTING DURING FLIGHT IN THE OVERHEAD BIN OF AIRCRAFT A SMALL AMOUNT OF KEROSES HAD LEAKED OUT AND CREATED FUMES IN THE CABIN.  THE SOURCE OF THE FUMES WERE DETERMINED AND FLIGHT ATTENDANTS PLACED THE LAMP IN A PLASTIC BAG AND STORED IN MORE SECURE PLACE IN CABIN.  UPON ARRIVAL AT SFO, THE OVERHEAD BIN WAS WIPED DOWN AND THE CABIN AIRED OUT.  THREE PASSENGERS WHO WERE NAUSEATED AND SUFFERING FROM HEADACHES WERE TREATED AND RELEASED BY AIRPORT DOCTOR AND PARAMEDICS.  ALI PAKNAHAL WHO THE LAMP BELONGED, SAID HE HAD FORGOTTEN TO DRAIN THE EXCESS KEROSENE FROM THE LAMP BEFORE GETTING TO THE AIRPORT IN PHX AND HE WAS AWARE THAT THIS IS CONSIDERED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column168: WHILE LOADING TRAILER 19-367 CHECKER TIM DAVIS IN ATTEMPT TO REARRANGE A SKID ON THIS TRAILER PUNCTURED TWO 55 GALLON DRUMS WITH HIS FORKLIFT BLADES.  AWAITING DISPOSITION BY WASTE MANAGEMENT TEAM-BRYSON RECOVERY SERV.  A MECHANIC ON THE SCENE RUBBED UP AGAINST MULE DURING CLEANUP.  HE WAS CARRIED TO BAPIST MINOR MEDICAL FOR TREATMENT OF BURNS.

N & M TRANSFER DRIVER JAMES PALMBACH WAS HEADING NORTHBOUND ON U.S. HWY 41.  AT APPROXIATELY 2100 HOURS, ON 9/24/91, HE WAS PULLED OVER BY SHERIFF'S DEPUTY ROY JASTER OF THE WASHINGTON COUNTY SHERIFFS DEPT.  THE APPROXIMATE LOCATION IS ABOUT 5 MILES NORTH OF LORIMA, WISCONSIN, NEAR THE INTERSECTION OF 41 AND 49.  THE DEPUTY ADVISED THE DRIVER THAT HE HAD PULLED HIM OVER BECAUSE OF A FLICKERING RIGHT TAIL LIGHT.  UPON EXAMINATION OF THE TAIL LIGHTS THE DEPUTY NOTICED THE CORROSIVE 1760 PLACARDS AND REQUESTED TO DO AN OPEN DOOR INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER.  UPON INSPECTING THE PORTAFEED CONTAINER, IT WAS APPARENT THAT A SMALL LEAK HAD BEGAN ON THE TOP COVER OF THE CONTAINER.  A SMALL STAIN WAS NOTICED ON THE WOODEN FLOOR OF THE TRAILER, POSSIBLY EQUIVALENT TO ONE PINT.  THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER LISTED ON THE BILL OF LADING DID NOT ANSWER WHEN NOTIFIED BY THE SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT.

ON MONDAY, SEPTEMBER 30, 1991, OUR DRIVER WAS LOADING A LOAD OF RQ, HAZARDOUS WASTE LIQUID N.O.S. (METAL HYDROXIDE SLUDGE) AT ALUMINUM COMPANY OF AMERICA IN ALCOA CENTER, PA.  AS THE MATERIAL FILLED TO THE TOP OF THE TANKER, APPROXIMATELY TWO TO THREE QUARTS OF MATERIAL LEAKED OUT OF THE MIDDLE MANWAY ON THE TOP OF THE TANKER. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP WITH FLOOR DRY AND PLACED BACK INTO THE TANKER.  BOB WALKER OF ALUMINUM COMPANY OF AMERICA WAS NOTIFIED AND SAID THAT THE AREA HAD BEEN CLEANED UP PROPERLY AND WAS IN ORDER. THE DRIVER PROPERLY SECURED THE TANKER FOR TRANSPORT AND THE LOAD WAS RETURNED SAFELY TO THE ENVIRITE FACILITY.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) L.D. LIBBY WAS NOTIFIED BY B.A. BISSEL, UNION PACIFIC MOTOR FREIGHT, ADVISING THAT TRAILER NONZ 452905 WAS LEAKING. SSA/HM LIBBY RESPONDED AND EXTERIOR INSEPCTION OF THE TRAILER DETERMINED THE LEAK TO BE IN THE FORWARD RIGHT SIDE PORTION OF THE TRAILER.  SSA/HM LIBBY REMOVED SEAL PETROLITE 003083 AND INTERIOR INSPECTION WAS CONDUCTED. SSA/HM FOUND 1 DRUM FLUDEX 0169 TO HAVE A LOOSE BUNG AND LIQUID PRODUCT ON THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  BUNG WAS TIGHTENED AND LIQUID WAS WIPED UP. SSA/HM LIBBY ALSO FOUND ONE 55 GALLON METAL DRUM, LABELED FLAMMABLE LIQUID, KONTOL CORROSION INHIBITOR, WHICH WAS CRUSHED AT THE BOTTOM AND HAD LEAKED CONTENTS. SSH/HM LIBBY CONTACTED TOM GILMAN, TRANSPORTATION MANAGER OF PETROLITE AND BRIEFED HIM ON THE INCIDENT.  MR. GILMAN COORDINATED THE CLEANUP AND DECONTAMINATION OF THE TRAILER THROUGH FRED CHRISTIE, TERMINAL MANAGER, LYNDEN TRANSPORT.  ARCTIC PACKAGING OF SEATTLE, WASHINGTON WAS CONTRACTED FOR CLEANUP/DISPOSITION.

MANAGER/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE R.M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED BY YARDMASTER (LLOYD HURST) THAT SWITCH CREW REPORTED A SMALL CONTINUOUS LEAK FROM TOP OF CAR GATX 98821. IN COMPANY OF SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) C.L. HILL AN INSPECTION WAS MADE OF THE CAR.  REMOVED (INTACT SEAL) UP Z 338176 FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND FOUND THE BALL VALVE ON THE LIQUID LINE 1/4TH OPEN AND ALSO THE PLUG IN THE VALVE PORT WAS PARTIALLY THREADED INTO PORT.  VALVE WAS CLOSED AND PLUG MADE WRENCH TIGHT.  THE HEAT OF THE DAY CAUSED A SLIGHT VAPOR PRESSURE THAT ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO PERCOLATE OUT. AFTER SECURING, SEAL MPRR 01-434798 WAS APPLIED.  THE RELEASED PRODUCT WAS VAPORIZING BEFORE REACHING THE GROUND. CHEMTREC (JIM LONG) AND TRAIN MANAGEMENT WERE NOTIFIED.

column168: ON 9/18/91 AT 0920 MT. DARRYL BALLARD, A YARD CLERK FOR THE BIRMINGHAM SOUTHERN RAILROAD COMPANY, OBSERVED A SMALL DRIP UNDER TANK CAR ACFX 89911. MR. KEITH GRAHAM OF ALLIED CHEMICAL WAS CALLED TO 34TH STREET YARD TO FIX SAID LEAK.  ATTACHED IS A COPY OF TRAINMANSTER JOHN M. D'ALESIO'S REPORT. TANK CAR ACFX 89911 WAS PLACED FROM ALLIED CHEMICAL LEASED STORAGE AREA AT BSRR 34TH ST. YARD TO ALLIED CHEMICAL PLANT ON 1/25/91.  ON 8/23/91, ACFX 89911 WAS PLACED BACK IN STORAGE AREA ON BSRR PROPERTY AT WHICH TIME SAID LEAK WAS FOUND AND REPORTED. *NO ATTACHMENTS WITH THIS REPORT*

ON 9-23-91, AT APPROXIMATELY 8:30 A.M., THE TULSA IC&S DISTRICT RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 75 GALLONS OF MINERAL SPIRITS AT A CUSTOMER LOCATION. (MOLINE PAINT)  THE MINERAL SPIRITS SPILLED FROM THE TRANSPORT AS IT OVERFILLED ONTO AN EARTH AND GRASS AREA.  THE DRIVER CONNECTED HOSES TO PUMP INCORRECTLY CAUSING PRODUCT TO BE PUMPED FROM CUSTOMER'S TANK INTO COMPARTMENT ON TANK TRAILER. I CALLED ASHLAND 800 EMERGENCY NUMBER AT APPROXIMATELY 8:45 A.M. AND TALKED TO BILL OLASIN AND INFORMED HIM ABOUT WHAT I PLANNED TO DO. I RESPONDED TO THE SITE WITH BILL INHOLE OF SOONER EMERGENCY SERVICES TO ACCESS SPILL AND CLEAN UP AT APPROXIMATELY 9:30 A.M.  BILL AND I BOTH AGREED THAT THE MATERIAL HAD SPREAD AS FAR AS IT WAS GOING TO.  I RETURNED TO THE PLANT AND AT THIS TIME ALL AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

DOCKMAN PICKED UP THE CARTON AND THE BOTTOM OF THE CARTON FELL OPEN CAUSING TWO GLASS JUGS TO FALL OUT AND BREAK WHEN THEY HIT THE CONCRETE FLOOR.  CLEANED UP BY FOUR SEASONS AND PLACED INTO RECOVERY DRUMS. RETURNING TO THE SHIPPER PER JIM PUGH.

OUR VEHICLE WAS INVOLVED IN A MINOR TRAFFIC ACCIDENT WHICH CAUSED THE LOAD TO SHIFT AND THE TRUCK TO OVERTURN.  THE DOME LID ON THE TANK LEAKED 25 GALLONS OF DIESEL OUT WHILE THE TRUCK WAS UPSIDE DOWN.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZMAT CLEANED UP THE FUEL.  THE VEHICLE WAS TAKEN TO ZERO BUTANE AND WASHED. ACCIDENT REPORT TO HAZMAT NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  LOG# 89493 JIM BOWMAR NOTE: ARKANSAS STATE POLICE REPORT STATES 1,000 GALLONS OF #2 DIESEL FUEL WAS SPILLED.  THIS WAS THE TOTAL GALLONS OF DIESEL ON THE TRUCK.  ONLY 25 GALLONS WAS SPILLED.

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) T.M. ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED BY YARD PERSONNEL AT ALEXANDRIA, LA, THAT A LARGE VAPOR CLOUD WAS COMING FROM THE TOP OF ARIX 1141. SSA/HM ROBINSON RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS A VAPOR RELEASE COMING FROM THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY.  MR OTTO WORTH, SERVICE TECHNICIAN FOR AIRCO, RESPONDED AND INSTALLED AN AUXILIARY VALVE AND SAFETY RELIEF VALVE ONTO THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY WHICH SECURED THE VAPOR RELEASE.  THE CAR WAS REGISTERING 51 PSI AND REMAINING PRODUCT WAS IN SOLID OR DRY ICE CONDITION.  THE CAR REMAINED ISOLATED AT THE ALEXANDRIA YARD SO PRESSURE COULD REBUILD INSIDE THE CAR.  AS PRESSURE WAS REGAINED AND THE CARBON DIOXIDE RETURNED TO LIQUID FORM, IT WAS TRANSFERRED TO CARGO TANK TRUCKS.  WHEN CAR WAS COMPLETELY EMPTIED, AUXILIARY VALVE AND SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS REMOVED, THE FAILED RUPTURE DISC WAS REPLACED AND THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY PROPERLY REASSEMBLED. CHEMTREC, LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AND ALEXANDRIA FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE NOTIFIED.

column168: MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE, R.M. STINE, WAS NOTIFIED BY NEFF YARDMASTER THAT THE SWITCH CREW ON YKC87 HAD REPORTED A VAPOR AROUND TOP FITTINGS ON CAR UCLX 30107 AS IT WAS BEING YARDED. MANAGER STINE RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE VENT FLANGE WAS EQUIPPED WITH A GATX 261-53 SPLASH DEFLECTOR/DISC RETAINER.  MANAGER STINE REMOVED INSPECTION PLUG AND NOTED THE "OSECO" DISC APPEARED IN TACT, HOWEVER, THERE WAS A HISSING SOUND COMING FROM THE FLANGE.  THE CAR WAS DE-PRESSURIZED AND REMOVAL OF THE DEFLECTOR DETERMINED THAT THE ENTIRE EDGE OF THE DISC WAS CRACKED AND BROKEN AS A RESULT OF THE THREE SECUREMENT BOLTS BEING TOO TIGHT.  MANAGER STINE INSTALLED AND SECURED A NEW OSECO 135 LB TEST DISC WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  MR. JIM LONG AT CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.

ON 09/14/91, SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) J.K. JENSEN WAS CONTACTED BY GAYLORD POFF, WEST YARD HUMPMASTER, ADVISING THAT TRAILER NUMBER XTRZ 656901, FLATCAR NUMBER KTTX 251902, WAS LEAKING. SA/HM JENSEN RESPONDED AND MET WITH LARRY WILDER, MANAGER OF YARD OPEATIONS.  TRAILER WAS ISOLATED AND SA/HM JENSEN REMOVED KELLER SEAL 6772693.  INSPECTION DETERMINED TWO 55 GALLONS DRUMS WERE LEAKING, ONE WHICH WAS COLLAPSED HALFWAY UP FROM THE BOTTOM.  BRACING WAS BROKEN AND LOAD SHIFT HAD OCCURRED. SA/HM FRANK LERCH WAS CONTACTED FOR ASSISTANCE.  SA/HM LERCH CONTACTED TOM FLORES, CHEMTREC, AND ELDON KELSO, UNION PACIFIC TRAIN MANAGEMENT.  SA/HM LERCH AND SA/HM JENSEN PLACED DRUMS IN SALVAGE DRUMS AND PATCHED PUNCTURES.  HINTONS LOCK AND ALARM OF NORTH PLATTE WAS CONTRACTED TO REPOSITION LOAD AND TWO MORE DRUMS WERE FOUND PUNCTURED DURING REPOSITIONING.  THESE TWO WERE ALSO PLACED IN SALVAGE DRUMS AND PATCHED. UNION PACIFIC SEAL C-53596 WAS PLACED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.

column168: CGI DOCKMAN, JACK CONSIDINE, WENT INTO DOOR 228 TO LOAD A SHIPMENT.  IN THE PROCESS, HE SPEARED A CARTON OF ORGANIC PEROXIDE. THE TRAILER CONTAINING THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY MOVED TO AN ISOLATED AREA OF THE DOCK ON THE WEST END.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND PLACED IN AN OVERPAK DRUM. HERITAGE INDUSTRIES WAS CALLED FOR DISPOSITION.

column25: DU PONT E I DE NEMOURS & CO
column168: DURING AN INTERCHANGE INSPECTION, OUR CAR INSPECTOR OBSERVED VAPORS AND MATERIAL BEING RELEASED FROM THE TOP OF A TANK CAR (UTLX 74632).  NONE OF THE MATERIAL REACHED THE GROUND.  IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 3 TO 5 LBS. OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  OUR CAR INSPECTOR IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE ASS'T. TRAINMASTER AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE FOR A B&P TRAIN CREW TO MOVE THE CAR TO AN ISOLATED AREA FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND REPAIR.  THE FOLLOWING NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE: 2200 - RELEASE OCCURRED, 2203 - ASS'T TRAINMASTER ADVISED, 2205 - B&P DISPATCHER CALLED, 2215 - B&P GENERAL MANAGERS CALLED, 2245 - CHEMTREC CALLED, 2230 - B&P CAR DEPARTMENT CALLED, 2305 - B&P HUMAN RESOURCES DEPARTMENT CALLED, 2308 - B&P SAFETY DIRECTOR CALLED, 2310 - FRA (CAMBRIDGE) CALLED, 2326 - DUPONT HAZMAT CALLED, 2328 - FRA (PAT REILLY) CALLED. DUPONT'S HAZMAT TEAM ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 0200 HOURS, AND PROCEEDED TO INSPECT/REPAIR THE CAR BY REPLACING THE DOME COVER GASKET AND TIGHTENING THE DOME COVER BOLTS AT APPROXIMATELY 0250 HOURS.  REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED AT 0400 HOURS ANE THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR SERVICE. NYS DEC WAS NOTIFIED AT 0930 HOURS.  THERE WERE NO ENVIRONMENTAL CONCERNS. AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE, THREE B&P RR EMPLOYEE WHO WERE THOUGHT TO HAVE BEEN EXPOSED TO THE VAPORS WERE TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL WHERE THEY WERE EXAMINED AND RELEASED.

TANK CAR AT NASHVILLE, TN WAS DISCOVERED VENTING YELLOWISH VAPORS WITH A STRONG ODOR.  CAR WAS ISOLATED.  THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED AND THE CITY FIRE DEPT HAZMAT TEAM NOTIFIED.  FIRE DEPT. REPORTED CAR LEAKING FROM SEAM WHERE DOME ATTACHED TO TANK.  CSXT HAZMAT MGR. W P HARRISON RESPONDED FROM ATLANTA, GA.  THE SHIPPER RESPONDED AND FOUND LEAKAGE AT GASKET BETWEEN THE PRESSURE PLATE AND TANK NOZZLE PHLANGE.  LEAK WAS STOPPED BY PATCHING AROUND GASKET.  CAR WAS MOVED TO NEARBY CONSIGNEE TO BE UNLOADED.  SHIPPER REPS. STAYED WITH CAR UNTIL IT WAS UNLOADED.

column168: TRAILER (CARGO TANK) BMI 181920 HAD BEEN LOADED FROM RAILROAD TANK CAR UTLX 48208.  LOADING OPERATION WAS COMPLETED WITHOUT INCIDENT.  HOWEVER, WHEN LOADER DISCONNECTED HOSE FROM BOTTOM VALVE ON TRAILER, HE FAILED TO COMPLETELY DESENGAGE A RETAINING SEAL.  WHEN THE PUMP WAS MOVED, THIS ACTION PULLED ON THE BOTTOM VALVE ON THE TRAILER AND DAMAGED THE VALVE CAUSING THE RELEASE.  THE RELEASE OCCURRED ONTO ASPHALT AND WAS CONTAINED BY EARTH DAMS AND SORBENTS.  ALTHOUGH A SMALL AMOUNT OF TOLUENE REACHED STORM DRAINS, THESE DRAINS WERE PLUGGED AND PUMPED OUT SO NO WATERWAYS WERE AFFECTED.  SPILL OCCURRED ON CSXT PROPERTY OPERATED BULK DISTRIBUTION CENTERS.  SITE CONTACT IS ROBERT URBAN (301/237-2371).

column168: ON 09/22/91 AT 0400 HOURS, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) R.D. FORDEMWALT WAS NOTIFIED BY RICK BROWN, TRAIN MANAGEMENT, THAT THE NPBAT 20 TRAIN HAD DERAILED AT 0330 HOURS BETWEEN CLEFT AND ORCHARD, ID, AND TWO CARS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, ARGON GAS WERE INVOLVED. SSA/HM FORDEMWALT ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT 0640 HOURS AND OBSERVED TANK CAR, ACFX 13202 LYING ON ITS LEFT SIDE SPILLING LIQUID OUT THE DAMAGED VALVES AND PIPING IN THE CONTROL BOX. UNION PACIFIC REPRESENTATIVES ON THE SCENE INCLUDED LEO TIERNEY, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DIRECTOR; DEAN WHITELY, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIAL AGENT, AND JIM BRIDGER, SUPERINTENDENT, ODAHO. JEROME BLAHA, MATLACK TRANSPORTATION COMPANY, ARRIVED AND TRANSFERRED CONTENTS OF SCXU 872195 TO BULKTAINER UPU 630040.  AFTER TRANSFER OF PRODUCT, SCXU 872195 WAS REINSPECTED AND DETEMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS FROM A HOLE DRILLED THROUGH THE TANK TO ANCHOR PATCH WHEN PATCH WAS APPLIED.  MR.  JOE SWEIGERT, SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE WAS NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: AT ABOUT 11:25 A.M., SEPTEMBER 17, 1991, OPERATOR, JIM FREEL, WAS DRIVING STAKE RACK VEHICLE NUMBER 1145 NORTH ON GENESEE STREET, UTICA, NY WHEN HE WAS FORCED TO AVOID AN ACCIDENT BY COMING TO COMING TO A SUDDEN STOP. OPERATOR DID THEN PARK THE TRUCK ON A BLACK TOP SURFACE LOCATED BEHIND THE NICE'N EASY, LOCATED AT 230 N. GENESEE ST., UTICA, NY.  DRIVER INSPECTED HIS CARGO AND DISCOVERED THAT A NAIL PROTRUDING FROM A PALLET HAD PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM OF A 15 GALLON POLY DELDRUM WHICH RESULTED IN THE LOSS OF TWO POUNDS OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID.  DELDRUM WAS TURNED WITH PUNCTURE IN THE UPRIGHT POSITION.  DRIVER CONTACTED THE DISPATCHER WHO IN TURN DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM TO THE SCENE.  CLEAN UP CONSISTED OF NEUTRALIZEING SPILL ON BED OF TRUCK AND PARKING SURFACE WITH SODA ASH. CONTENTS FROM DAMAGED DELDRUM WERE TRANSFERRED TO A SECOND DELDRUM. NEUTRALIZED SWEEPINGS AND REPACKAGED HYDROCHLORIC ACID WERE RETURNED TO THE PLANT. SWEEPINGS WERE DILUTED WITH WATER AND INTRODUCED TO THE ELEMENTARY NEUTRALIZATION SYSTEM.  NET WEIGHT OF REPACKAGED ACID WAS ADJUSTED AND SUBSEQUENTLY SOLD. ACTION: TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS ALL EMPLOYEES HAD BEEN DIRECTED TO EXAMINE CONDITION OF PALLET PRIOR TO LOADING.
column172: Reusable molded polyethylene container without overpack RHNA*

column168: ON 9/12/91, AT APPROXIMATELY 2340, WE WERE INFORMED BY A RAMP AGENT THAT THERE HAD BEEN A SPILL OF SOME SORT ON FLIGHT #306, THE FINAL TERMINATOR AIRCRAFT FROM LOS ANGELES.  THERE HAD BEEN A BOX CONTAINING SOME TOOLS, PAINT AND A VINYL WASH SOLVENT IN THE FORWARD BIN.  THE VINYL WASH HAD LEAKED AND SATURATED THE BOX AND CREATED A STRONG ODOR IN THE BIN.  THE LABEL ON THE CAN SHOWED IT TO BE "HIGHLY FLAMMABLE". AT THAT TIME, THE RAMP AGENT NOTIFIED THE MANAGER OF RAMP AND OPERATIONS OF THE INCIDENT.  HE WAS ADVISED TO CALL THE POLICE AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND INFORM THEM OF THE SITUATION.  THE CALL WAS MADE IMMEDIATELY TO THE ABOVE NAMED AGENCIES AND THEN THE BAGGAGE SERVICE OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED.

SA/HM JARA WAS INFORMED BY THE YARDMASTER THAT THE CAR WAS DUE TO DEPART FOR CAL AMMONIA WITHIN THE NEXT HALF HOUR WHICH IS LOCATED A SHORT DISTANCE FROM STOCKTON YARD.  YARDMASTER BARNES NOTIFIED CAL AMMONIA THAT THE CAR WAS EN ROUTE AND SA/HM JARA FOLLOWED GATX 49668 INTO CAL AMMONIA AND BRIEFED MR. R. SMITH UPON ARRIVAL. CHEMTREC, STOCKTON FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES WERE ALL NOTIFIED.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) DENNIS ALM WAS NOTIFIED BY YARDMASTER KEN BARNES THAT A CREW HAD REPORTED VAPORS IN THE UNION PACIFIC YARD, STOCKTON, CA.  YARDMASTER BARNES ALSO STATED THAT TRAINMASTER AL WALLACE REPORTED THAT VAPORS APPEARED TO BE COMING FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING OF GATX 49668.  SSA/HM ALM RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE SAFETY REFIEF DEVICE ON THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR WAS LEAKING A SLIGHT AMOUNT OF VAPOR.  ALL BOLTS WERE CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE TIGHT.  SSA/HM ALM NOTIFIED CAL AMMONIA AND SPOKE WITH MR. BOB SMITH.  MR. SMITH STATED A REPRESENTATIVE WOULD RESPOND.  MR. RON MADDOCK RESPONDED FROM CAL AMMONIA AND INSPECTED TANKCAR AND DETERMINED THAT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WOULD HAVE TO BE REPLACED.  TO ENSURE SAFETY, MR. MADDOCK RECOMMENDED THAT THE TANK CAR BE MOVED TO THE FACILITY FOR REPLACEMENT OF THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  SSA/HM ALM MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE THE CAR MOVED AS SOON AS POSSIBLE.  A SWITCH ENGINE TO MOVE THE CAR WOULD NOT BE AVAILABLE UNTIL 09/30/91 TO MOVE CAR TO CAL AMMONIA.  CHEMTREC, CALIFORNIA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE ALL NOTIFIED.

column42: ORGANIC PHOSPHATE, ORGANIC PHOSPHATE COMPOUND, OR ORGANIC PHOSPHORUS COMPOUND; SOLID OR DRY
column168: ON SEPTEMBER 11, 1991 ADVANCE TRANSPORTATION MADE A PICK UP OF 9,000 LBS. OF ORGANIC PHOSPHATE COMPOUND MIXTURE POISON B, NA 2783 FROM TERRA INTERNATIONAL INCORPORATED, 430 WEST CARMEL, CARMEL, INDIANA.  LATER AT THE INDIANAPOLIS TERMINAL, WHEN DOCKMEN RICHARD SIRCY AND DAVID MCDANIEL BEGAN UNLOADING THIS SHIPMENT, THEY NOTICED AFTER REMOVING THE THIRD PALLET THERE WAS POWDER LEAKING FROM IT.  AT THAT TIME THEY SET THE LEAKING PALLET BACK IN THE TRAILER AND CALLED FOR THE SUPERVISOR.  AT 1946 HOURS, PHONE CALLS WERE MADE TO THE APPROPRIATE CHAIN OF COMMAND INCLUDING CHEMTREC FOR PROPER PROCEDURE FOR DISPOSITION OF THE SPILL.  WE CALLED AMERICAN CYANAMID AND WERE ADVISED BY JOE MIDDIONE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CO-ORDINATOR TO CALL THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM FROM THE INDIANAPOLIS FIRE DEPARTMENT. THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM CLEANED UP 5 OUNCES ON THE DOCK AND PLACED IT IN A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE DRUM AND TWO OTHER SKIDS WERE LOADED BACK IN THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER WAS SECURED IN THE YARD.  DRUMS WERE PLACED AROUND THE TRAILER AND HAZARDOUS TAPE WAS RUN FROM DRUM TO DRUM TO SURROUND THE TRAILER TO WARN OF THE DANGER. THE DOCK WAS CLEARED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND ALL EMPLOYEES WERE PERMITTED BACK TO WORK AT 2245 HOURS.  DOCKMEN RICHARD SIRCY AND DAVID MCDANIEL WERE TAKEN TO WISHARD MEMORIAL HOSPITAL TO BE CHECKED OUT.  THEY WERE OKAY AND RELEASED. ON SEPTEMBER 12, GARY A. FINN PHD TECHNICAL SERVICE REPRESENTATIVE, CROP PROTECTION CHEMICALS DEPARTMENT, AMERICAN CYANAMID COMPANY HAD AN INSPECTION OF THE FREIGHT IN THE TRAILER.  HE ALSO ADVISED US THAT WE WERE VERY PRUDENT IN OUR ACTIONS.  WE WERE TOLD THAT THESE WERE LIKE BINS WITH CARTONS INSIDE THAT ARE HELD BY SOME KIND OF LOAD-LOCK, IN WHICH A SPRING COULD HAVE BROKE.  THIS IS WHY WE ARE UNABLE TO ANSWER QUESTIONS 30 THROUGH 43 VERY WELL.  WE NEVER GOT A CHANCE TO REALLY SEE OR CHECK THE FREIGHT CARTONS AND/OR BINS.  FURTHER INFORMATION WOULD HAVE TO BE SUPPLIED BY AMERICAN CYANAMID. OUR TERMINAL MANAGER IN INDIANAPOLIS, EDWARD WRIGHT, CALLED AMERICAN CYANAMID TO FIND OUT WHO WAS GOING TO TAKE THIS TRAILER BACK.  HE SPOKE WITH JOHN MCKINNEY AND BRIAN MNISH.  LATER JOHN ANDERSON ADVISED THAT THE LOAD SHOULD BE RETURNED TO AMERICAN CYANAMID, 3000 S. SHELBY, BUILDING 5, IN INDIANAPOLIS.  ON SEPTEMBER 17, 1991 THE LOAD WAS RETURNED.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: I PICKED THIS PACKAGE UP AT PD# 2, FOR A NEW HAZARDOUS MATERIAL LABEL AND SMELLED IT LEAKING.  I OPENED IT UP AND FOUND 6 OF THE 12 PLASTIC BOTTLES SPLIT EACH IN PLASTIC BAGS, SO THE OTHER CONTAINER DID NOT GET DAMAGED. REMOVED LEAKING BOTTLES WHICH HAD HAZARD-FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  PUT THEM IN A PLASTIC BAG IN THE OLD BOX IN A BAG AND DISPOSED OF IT.  THE REST OF THE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  IT WAS WRITING THE REPORTS AND DISCOVERED THAT THIS PACKAGE WAS A COD FOR $440.18, WAS REALLY AND RPS (ROADWAY PACKAGE).  THIS WAS SCRAPPED TO DOT REGULATIONS.  TALKED TO MIKE MOYER (HUB MANAGER) AND HE SAID TO RETURN IT, AS WE WOULD OUR DAMAGES.

ON 09/27/91, WHILE OFF LOADING FREIGHT I NOTICED A PRCULAIAR SMELL IN ONE OF THE BOXES SO I, SEPARATED THE PACKAGE AND CALLED THE SHIPPER TO VERIFY THE CONTENTS IN THE PACKAGE.  I WAS INFORMED IT WAS A PRINTER WITH INK (FLAMMABEL III) INSIDE.  THEN, 1 CALLED DANGEROUS GOODS AND REPORTED A DANGEROUS GOODS PACKAGE WITHOUT PROPER PAPER WORK THAT HAD LEAKED. (STATEMENT BY TERRY BECKLHEIMER).  AFTER DETERMINING AN APPARENT NON-DECLARED DG HAD BEEN UNCOVERED; THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED WHO INITIATED AN INVESTIGATION.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: 02:17 HOURS: RECEIVED A CALL FROM TOM STEELE, WRTC THAT TANK CAR GATX 300866 WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP.  02:30 HOURS: CONTACTED BERNIE HERNANDEZ.  CAR FOREMAN COLTON, AND HE DESCRIBED THAT THE LEAK WAS FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET AND THAT IT WAS LEAKING A SMALL STREAM.  HE ADVISED ME THAT HE TRIED TO TIGHTEN THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WITH A WRENCH.  BUT COULD NOT SUCCESSFULLY STOP THE LEAK.  03:00 HOURS:  CONTACTED  H.L BART AND HE ADVISED ME TO CHARTER TO THE SITE.  07:00 HOURS:  ARRIVED TO THE SITE AND WAS ADVISED THAT THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD REDUCED THE LEAK BY TIGHTENING THE TOP OPERATING BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  09:45 HOURS:  LEAK WAS REPAIRED BY REPLACING THE DEFECTIVE GASKET IN THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP AND WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column168: ON 09/18/91, YARDMASTER J. KASS NOTIFIED CHEMTREC THAT TANK CAR UTLX 630073 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP DURING MOVEMENT.  CHEMTREC NOTIFIED MR. R. HINTON OF VININGS INDUSTRIES AND MR. HINTON RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT. MANAGER OF MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE, JIM OSBURN, HAD INSPECTED THE CAR WHICH WAS NO LONGER LEAKING AND DETERMINED THAT THE MANWAY GASKET WAS OLD AND DETERIORATED.  UPON MR. HINTON'S ARRIVAL, GASKET WAS REPLACED WHICH SECURED THE CAR FOR MOVEMENT. SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS T.M. ROBINSON BRIEFED ALL PERSONNEL INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT TO ENSURE THAT THE POLICE AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT IS NOTIFIED FOR REPORTING PURPOSES.

SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) JOE JARA WAS NOTIFIED THAT CAR IAPX 1002 WAS LEAKING FROM THE DOME AREA.  SA/HM JARA RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE HOUSING WAS FULL OF CONDENSATION AND ICE HAD FORMED ON THE TOP.  AFTER ALLOWING SOME OF THE ICE TO MELT AWAY, THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE FROM THE LIQUID FILL LINE.  MR. LANDUCCI, EMERENCY REPAIRS FOR CARDOX DIVISION, RESPONDED AND ASSISTED SA/HM JARA IN REMOVING THE ICE FROM THE TOP.  AFTER ALL THE ICE WAS REMOVED INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS FROM A ONE INCH PLUG WHICH WAS CRACKED AT THE BASE.  THE LEAK WAS PLUGGED BY APPLYING A WET RAG TO THE AREA OF RELEASE AND CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT BACK TO CARDOX PLANT FOR OFFLOADING AND REPAIR.
